abstract: Sleep apnea and other problems that cause low oxygen saturation of blood during sleep may increase the risk of brain changes associated with dementia, a new study reports.
snippet: Sleep apnea and other problems that cause low oxygen saturation of blood during sleep may increase the risk of brain changes associated with dementia, a new study reports.
lead_paragraph: Poor sleep in older adults may be linked to brain changes associated with dementia, a new study has found.

abstract: Researchers have found that people diagnosed with diabetes in their 50’s are significantly more likely than others to suffer mental decline by their 70’s.
snippet: Researchers have found that people diagnosed with diabetes in their 50’s are significantly more likely than others to suffer mental decline by their 70’s.
lead_paragraph: Researchers have found that people diagnosed with diabetes in their 50’s are significantly more likely than others to suffer mental decline by their 70’s.
headline.main: Diabetes in Midlife Tied to Memory Problems Late in Life
headline.print_headline: Diabetes Can Spur Dementia

abstract: Mrs. Cochran, a former teacher, was in a nursing home when she became part of an unsuccessful attack ad against her husband, Senator Thad Cochran.
snippet: Mrs. Cochran, a former teacher, was in a nursing home when she became part of an unsuccessful attack ad against her husband, Senator Thad Cochran.
lead_paragraph: Rose Cochran, who was unwittingly thrust into the middle of a bitter primary campaign being waged by her husband, Senator Thad Cochran, in Mississippi this year, died on Friday at a hospice in Ridgeland, Miss. She was 73.

headline.main: Rose Cochran, a Figure in a Campaign Attack Video, Dies at 73
headline.print_headline: Rose Cochran, 73, a Figure in a Campaign Attack Video

abstract: A documentary presents a treatment for Alzheimer’s and other forms of dementia, while it offers profiles of people suffering from the disease.
snippet: A documentary presents a treatment for Alzheimer’s and other forms of dementia, while it offers profiles of people suffering from the disease.
lead_paragraph: The documentary “Do You Know What My Name Is?” introduces us to people with forms of dementia, like Alzheimer’s. It’s a condition that frightens many of us, because we’re worried that we’ll have it or will care for someone who has it, or because we’ve had experience with it. Films like “Away From Her” and the current release “Still Alice” meaningfully illustrate the challenges of the diagnosis.

abstract: One in five nursing home residents was involved in mistreatment of a neighbor in the previous month, a new study found.
snippet: One in five nursing home residents was involved in mistreatment of a neighbor in the previous month, a new study found.
lead_paragraph: It will not surprise people who spend time in nursing homes — who live or work there, who volunteer or visit family members — that residents can lash out at each other.
headline.main: Aggressive Neighbors in the Nursing Home

abstract: A number of conditions cause dementia-like symptoms, and doctors may have trouble diagnosing them. Still, the odds usually are low that an elderly family member can be made cognitively normal.
snippet: A number of conditions cause dementia-like symptoms, and doctors may have trouble diagnosing them. Still, the odds usually are low that an elderly family member can be made cognitively normal.
lead_paragraph: Maybe it’s something else.
headline.main: Is It Really Dementia?

abstract: Games spent gathering helmet fragments and supplying smelling salts.
snippet: Games spent gathering helmet fragments and supplying smelling salts.
lead_paragraph: WITH each new arrest of a National Football League star, I’ve joined our collective finger-wagging at the league and its players, all while repressing a gnawing guilt: As a 17-year-old ball boy for the 2003 Chicago Bears, I helped players achieve heights of on-field violence so brutal that off-field aftershocks were all but inevitable.

abstract: Alzheimer’s occurs more often among older people who have used benzodiazepines for long periods, researchers report.
snippet: Alzheimer’s occurs more often among older people who have used benzodiazepines for long periods, researchers report.
lead_paragraph: I swear I don’t go looking for alarming news about benzodiazepines, drugs widely prescribed for insomnia and anxiety. But it shows up with some frequency, so, mindful of your fervidly held views on the subject, I am donning a hazmat suit to bring you the latest findings from the medical journal BMJ.
headline.main: Study Links Anxiety Drugs to Alzheimer’s Disease

abstract: A documentary airing on PBS provides a cleareyed account of one family’s struggle with Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: A documentary airing on PBS provides a cleareyed account of one family’s struggle with Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: When the documentary filmmaker Banker White began turning his camera on his family in 2009, his mother had undertaken a project of great personal importance: She wanted to compile material for a book about her own mother, a Massachusetts painter named Marian Williams Steele, who died of Alzheimer’s disease in 2001.

headline.main: A Picture of Dementia

abstract: Suicide seems to be less common where the lithium is more plentiful in drinking water.
snippet: Suicide seems to be less common where the lithium is more plentiful in drinking water.
lead_paragraph: THE idea of putting a mind-altering drug in the drinking water is the stuff of sci-fi, terrorist plots and totalitarian governments. Considering the outcry that occurred when putting fluoride in the water was first proposed, one can only imagine the furor that would ensue if such a thing were ever suggested.

abstract: Why are patients with advanced dementia so often receiving “medications of questionable benefit”?
snippet: Why are patients with advanced dementia so often receiving “medications of questionable benefit”?
lead_paragraph: How sick and disabled, how far into advanced dementia, how close to death do elderly nursing home patients have to be before their physicians stop prescribing drugs that can cause uncomfortable side effects but show scant evidence of helping them?

abstract: What I’d thought was depression was really was something else.
snippet: What I’d thought was depression was really was something else.
lead_paragraph: She lay so still as I approached her bed, I thought she was asleep. Or dead. Her eyes were open. “Mom?” I asked. Her gaze tilted toward me, but she said nothing.

headline.main: Her Own Kind of Absence

abstract: The medicalization of food deprives the dying of some of the last remnants of the human experience: taste, smell, touch and connection to loved ones.
snippet: The medicalization of food deprives the dying of some of the last remnants of the human experience: taste, smell, touch and connection to loved ones.
lead_paragraph: The patient had dementia and could no longer swallow. The intricate workings of the muscles of her throat were failing, and she was no longer able to move food or liquids reliably into her stomach. Instead, they too frequently ended up in her lungs, and she drowned a little more with every swallow. She was admitted to my intensive care service with pneumonia from aspirated food that had turned the bottom part of her left lung into a wet sponge. Her blood oxygen levels had dropped so low that we had to support her breathing by inserting a tube.

abstract: A home health aide cannot sue a couple with dementia for an injury sustained while caring for them, the California Supreme Court has ruled.
snippet: A home health aide cannot sue a couple with dementia for an injury sustained while caring for them, the California Supreme Court has ruled.
lead_paragraph: The California Supreme Court has ruled that a home health aide may not sue a client with Alzheimer’s disease for an injury incurred on the job. The case is one of the first in the nation to assess legal remedies available to paid caregivers who work with Alzheimer’s patients at home.

abstract: Low vitamin D is associated with an increased risk for Alzheimer’s disease and other dementias, according to a new report.
snippet: Low vitamin D is associated with an increased risk for Alzheimer’s disease and other dementias, according to a new report.
lead_paragraph: Low vitamin D is associated with an increased risk for Alzheimer’s disease and other forms of dementia, according to a new report, though whether low vitamin D is a cause of the disorders remains unknown.

abstract: Researchers are finding no silver bullet for prevention of Alzheimer’s disease, only everyday changes we should all be making anyway.
snippet: Researchers are finding no silver bullet for prevention of Alzheimer’s disease, only everyday changes we should all be making anyway.
lead_paragraph: What we really want, if we’re honest, is a pill or a shot that would allow us to stop worrying about ever sinking into dementia.
headline.main: Small Changes, and Hopes, for Preventing Dementia

abstract: Know what level of care a person with dementia requires and which homes has the best programs and atmosphere. Also take into account your travel situation.
snippet: Know what level of care a person with dementia requires and which homes has the best programs and atmosphere. Also take into account your travel situation.
lead_paragraph: It took three tries before Leslie Reid-Green found a suitable nursing home for her 88-year-old mother, Bella Solomon, who has advanced dementia.

abstract: A premiere by Lisa Renée Coons about mental illness and dementia was a highlight of “Lines on a Point,” a program by the American Composers Orchestra.
snippet: A premiere by Lisa Renée Coons about mental illness and dementia was a highlight of “Lines on a Point,” a program by the American Composers Orchestra.
lead_paragraph: Discerning the correlation between a composer’s description of a new piece and its actual sound is not always easy. But there was no such ambiguity in “Vera’s Ghosts” by Lisa Renée Coons, which received its premiere on Thursday evening at Zankel Hall by the American Composers Orchestra, conducted by George Manahan.

abstract: Rayfield Wright, who sustained countless blows to the head during 13 seasons with the Cowboys, said N.F.L. players do not know what awaits in retirement.
snippet: Rayfield Wright, who sustained countless blows to the head during 13 seasons with the Cowboys, said N.F.L. players do not know what awaits in retirement.
lead_paragraph: WILLOW PARK, Tex. — The Hall of Famer Rayfield Wright’s increasingly imperfect memory retains an indelible image of his first N.F.L. start.

headline.main: For a Cowboys Star With Dementia, Time Is Running Out
headline.print_headline: Time Running Out

abstract: Leslie Jean-Bart makes pictures of reflections on the shore and boardwalk, where the image changes in an instant, and nothing is ever fully under his control.
snippet: Leslie Jean-Bart makes pictures of reflections on the shore and boardwalk, where the image changes in an instant, and nothing is ever fully under his control.
lead_paragraph: Like a cooling salve, the Atlantic waves lapping onto the Coney Island shore had a calming effect on Leslie Jean-Bart. About eight years ago he had gone there seeking peace, his photographic career on hold as he dealt with his mother’s dementia.

abstract: Seven former players said the proposed settlement, which includes an uncapped amount of damages for players with severe neurological disorders, would fail to compensate many retirees.
snippet: Seven former players said the proposed settlement, which includes an uncapped amount of damages for players with severe neurological disorders, would fail to compensate many retirees.
lead_paragraph: Seven former N.F.L. players accused the N.F.L. and the lawyers representing more than 4,500 retirees of failing to justify how they reached their proposed settlement that includes an uncapped amount of damages for players with severe neurological disorders.

abstract: Exercise may help to keep the brain robust in people who have an increased risk of developing Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: Exercise may help to keep the brain robust in people who have an increased risk of developing Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: Exercise may help to keep the brain robust in people who have an increased risk of developing Alzheimer’s disease, according to an inspiring new study. The findings suggests that even moderate amounts of physical activity may help to slow the progression of one of the most dreaded diseases of aging.
headline.main: Can Exercise Reduce Alzheimer’s Risk?
headline.print_headline: Keeping Alzheimeru2019s at Bay

abstract: Most of the victims were patients in their 70s and 80s, many of whom had been hospitalized for dementia or stroke complications.
snippet: Most of the victims were patients in their 70s and 80s, many of whom had been hospitalized for dementia or stroke complications.
lead_paragraph: SEOUL, South Korea — A fire broke out at a hospital annex in South Korea early Wednesday, killing 21 people and injuring seven others and further rattling a country still traumatized by a recent ferry disaster. The police were holding a patient in connection with the fire.
headline.main: Patient Is Held After Fire at South Korea Hospital Kills 21
headline.print_headline: Patient Is Held After Fire at South Korea Hospital Kills 21

abstract: Dementia is not something we doctors talk much about. We all have many patients with dementia — and more every year — but we never seem to chat about it the way we discuss kidney disease or cancer treatment.
snippet: Dementia is not something we doctors talk much about. We all have many patients with dementia — and more every year — but we never seem to chat about it the way we discuss kidney disease or cancer treatment.
lead_paragraph: “A fate worse than death,” my colleague muttered to me as we examined an elderly man admitted to the hospital with severe dementia.

abstract: The protein, which switches off at birth, reawakens in some older brains, protecting people from the memory and thinking problems of dementia, researchers say.
snippet: The protein, which switches off at birth, reawakens in some older brains, protecting people from the memory and thinking problems of dementia, researchers say.
lead_paragraph: It is one of the big scientific mysteries of Alzheimer’s disease: Why do some people whose brains accumulate the plaques and tangles so strongly associated with Alzheimer’s not develop the disease?

abstract: Using fear to help protect patients with dementia.
snippet: Using fear to help protect patients with dementia.
lead_paragraph: I am an advocate for nursing-home residents. A new technique to control the wandering of dementia patients involves placing black floor mats in front of unsafe areas, such as outside exits. Due to a fear of falling, persons with dementia will not walk on dark spaces on the floor (they tend to see them as holes). This is an alternative to antipsychotic drugs and lockdown units. Since this technique uses fear and a disability to guide behavior, but with the intent of safety, is it ethical? LISA MARIE HAYES, HOUSTON

abstract: Because the N.F.L.’s recent settlement promises payments to an unknown number of players, the $765 million called for in the deal could run out faster than expected.
snippet: Because the N.F.L.’s recent settlement promises payments to an unknown number of players, the $765 million called for in the deal could run out faster than expected.
lead_paragraph: As intriguing football matchups go, Sunday’s Super Bowl has nothing on one looming down the turnpike in federal court in Philadelphia — with Judge Anita B. Brody the ultimate referee.

abstract: Frequently a result of dementia, anosognosia is the inability to recognize one’s own impairment — a phenomenon caregivers know too well.
snippet: Frequently a result of dementia, anosognosia is the inability to recognize one’s own impairment — a phenomenon caregivers know too well.
lead_paragraph: Soon after his wife was diagnosed with frontotemporal dementia, Bill Floyd consulted a neurologist who had been a member of his church. People with this illness don’t know they have it, the doctor warned. They don’t understand that anything is wrong.

abstract: Watching over loved ones with dementia frequently presents new challenges, and a new book focuses on caregivers and the stressful situations they face.
snippet: Watching over loved ones with dementia frequently presents new challenges, and a new book focuses on caregivers and the stressful situations they face.
lead_paragraph: Paul Divinigracia does not consider himself a saint. But to observe how he cares for his wife, Virgie, now 11 years into Alzheimer’s disease, you might think otherwise.

headline.main: Caring for the Alzheimer’s Caregiver

abstract: A new study suggests that Alzheimer’s causes six times as many deaths as the official statistics would indicate.
snippet: A new study suggests that Alzheimer’s causes six times as many deaths as the official statistics would indicate.
lead_paragraph: A provocative new study has suggested that Alzheimer’s disease causes six times as many deaths as the official statistics would indicate.
headline.main: High Mortality From Alzheimer’s Disease
headline.print_headline: High Mortality From Alzheimer’s Disease

abstract: The victims were mostly older dementia patients, and their deaths further traumatized a country still shaken by the recent ferry disaster.
snippet: The victims were mostly older dementia patients, and their deaths further traumatized a country still shaken by the recent ferry disaster.
lead_paragraph: SEOUL, South Korea — A fire broke out at a hospital annex in southwestern South Korea early Wednesday, killing 21 people and injuring seven others and further rattling a country still traumatized by a recent ferry disaster.
headline.main: 21 Die in Fire at Hospital in South Korea
headline.print_headline: 21 Die in Fire at Hospital in South Korea

abstract: The American Geriatrics Society says medical evidence is scant for five common treatments in the elderly.
snippet: The American Geriatrics Society says medical evidence is scant for five common treatments in the elderly.
lead_paragraph: It tells you something about American health care that scores of medical societies have joined a major campaign aimed at telling patients and doctors what not to do.
headline.main: Geriatricians Question Five Common Treatments

abstract: Doctors in Ohio have developed a simple four-page quiz that can help reveal dementia early on, allowing patients to get their lives in order.
snippet: Doctors in Ohio have developed a simple four-page quiz that can help reveal dementia early on, allowing patients to get their lives in order.
lead_paragraph: Liz Arledge is all too familiar with the ravages of dementia. Her mother died of Alzheimer’s, and one of her brothers has been found to have the progressive brain disease as well.
headline.main: A Test for the Early Detection of Alzheimer’s Disease

abstract: In “Archaeology of a Woman,” Sally Kirkland plays an ex-newspaper columnist battling dementia while a murder mystery unfolds.
snippet: In “Archaeology of a Woman,” Sally Kirkland plays an ex-newspaper columnist battling dementia while a murder mystery unfolds.
lead_paragraph: Not everything in a movie needs to make sense, but when almost nothing does, it’s a problem. Even so, what the publicity notes are pleased to call a “disconcerting narrative structure” is far from the only issue with “Archaeology of a Woman,” Sharon Greytak’s confounding blend of long-ago murder and present-day dementia.

headline.main: A Weakness for Cops, a Crime to Solve
headline.print_headline: Archaeology of a Woman

abstract: Irving and his grandson Micah share a special bond that Irving’s age and dementia cannot break.
snippet: Irving and his grandson Micah share a special bond that Irving’s age and dementia cannot break.
lead_paragraph: At 91, my father, Irving Effron, can barely remember his children’s names, though he has acute recollections of long-forgotten battles that he fought as a Marine in the Philippines during World War II. My mother, Ruth, grieves for the loss of the guy who swept her off her feet on a Rockaway beach the summer after he came home from the war. That guy was here up until a few years ago, when dementia set in and Irving’s rare good days became something to cherish, even as his bad days became more numerous.

headline.main: For Micah’s Birthday, His Grandfather’s Blessing

abstract: A new memoir by the 86-year-old Gordie Howe, one of the most prolific scorers in hockey history.
snippet: A new memoir by the 86-year-old Gordie Howe, one of the most prolific scorers in hockey history.
lead_paragraph: Gordie Howe had three teeth knocked out in his first game with the Detroit Red Wings in 1946. By the time he retired from the National Hockey League in 1980, at age 52, he had sustained at least 14 broken noses and, by his estimation, required more than 300 stitches to repair his face. He was once kicked in the temple and, so woozy he couldn’t see straight, missed the entry to the team bench by three feet.

abstract: As I get older, I collect examples of others’ memory lapses, as signs that anyone can misplace things without fear of showing mental decline.
snippet: As I get older, I collect examples of others’ memory lapses, as signs that anyone can misplace things without fear of showing mental decline.
lead_paragraph: I’m always on the alert for any proof I can muster that my missteps, mistakes, misunderstandings and failures of memory are just the stuff of normal human-being-ness — and not the signs of mental decline as I age.

headline.main: On Losing It (or Not)

abstract: Calculating how much medication an older patient should get and on what schedule is often complicated by erratic meals, vision loss, depression and dementia.
snippet: Calculating how much medication an older patient should get and on what schedule is often complicated by erratic meals, vision loss, depression and dementia.
lead_paragraph: Most people with diabetes are treated with drugs (notably metformin) that don’t put them at risk of unusually low blood sugar, or hypoglycemia, a potentially dangerous side effect. But as patients age and develop other chronic medical conditions, it becomes more difficult for them to tolerate these medications.
headline.main: Older People Often Overtreated for Diabetes, Study Suggests

abstract: The singer and songwriter performs a song from her one-woman musical play.
snippet: The singer and songwriter performs a song from her one-woman musical play.
lead_paragraph: This week’s video features a musical number from “My Mother Has 4 Noses,” a one-woman musical play written and performed by the singer-songwriter Jonatha Brooke. In the show, directed by Jeremy B. Cohen, Ms. Brooke weaves together storytelling and songs about caring for her mother, a Christian Scientist who suffered from dementia and cancer. In this scene she sings the number “Time,” about being unprepared for her mother’s death. She accompanies herself on a kalimba, an African thumb piano. The show continues through May 4 at the Duke on 42nd Street.
headline.main: In Performance: Jonatha Brooke of ‘My Mother Has 4 Noses’

abstract: Three more retired hockey players have sued the N.H.L. alleging that the league allowed fighting and promoted violence while minimizing the risk of head injuries.
snippet: Three more retired hockey players have sued the N.H.L. alleging that the league allowed fighting and promoted violence while minimizing the risk of head injuries.
lead_paragraph: Three more retired hockey players have sued the N.H.L. alleging that the league allowed fighting and promoted violence while minimizing the risk of head injuries. The three are Dave Christian, who was on the United States Olympic team for the 1980 Miracle on Ice and who played 1,009 N.H.L. games; Reed Larson, the highest-scoring American defenseman in N.H.L. history when he left the league in 1990; and Bill Bennett.

abstract: Some older people with impaired vision begin to see people and objects that aren’t there. It’s not dementia, but a condition called Charles Bonnet Syndrome.
snippet: Some older people with impaired vision begin to see people and objects that aren’t there. It’s not dementia, but a condition called Charles Bonnet Syndrome.
lead_paragraph: A few days after I wrote about conditions that can mimic dementia, reader Sue Murray emailed me from Westchester County. Her subject line: “Have you heard of Charles Bonnet Syndrome?”

abstract: The singer-songwriter Jonatha Brooke, who wrote “My Mother Has 4 Noses,” performs it at the Duke on 42nd Street.
snippet: The singer-songwriter Jonatha Brooke, who wrote “My Mother Has 4 Noses,” performs it at the Duke on 42nd Street.
lead_paragraph: Deep into Jonatha Brooke’s solo theater piece the other night, a gentle wave of sniffles swelled through the audience at the Duke on 42nd Street, where a daughter’s love and loyalty were on tender display.

abstract: Assuming the judge approves it, the accord on the $760 million settlement could determine how retirees with head trauma are compensated.
snippet: Assuming the judge approves it, the accord on the $760 million settlement could determine how retirees with head trauma are compensated.
lead_paragraph: The N.F.L. and lawyers for the more than 4,000 former players who said the league hid from them the dangers of repeated hits to the head have agreed on the details of a $760 million settlement that could determine how retirees with head trauma are compensated.

abstract: The statements are the league’s most unvarnished admission yet that the sport’s professional participants sustain severe brain injuries at far higher rates than the general population.
snippet: The statements are the league’s most unvarnished admission yet that the sport’s professional participants sustain severe brain injuries at far higher rates than the general population.
lead_paragraph: The National Football League, which for years disputed evidence that its players had a high rate of severe brain damage, has stated in federal court documents that it expects nearly a third of retired players to develop long-term cognitive problems and that the conditions are likely to emerge at “notably younger ages” than in the general population.

abstract: Often low blood sugar, not raised levels, is the more pressing problem among elderly patients with diabetes.

lead_paragraph: Most of the time, the older woman seemed sharp. But increasingly, she became confused and disoriented — a case of “intermittent dementia,” one doctor speculated. Further tests were ordered, and then another diagnosis emerged.
headline.main: Hypoglycemia Rising in Older People With Diabetes

headline.main: For Stone Phillips, a Focus on the Home Front

abstract: Two brothers in France deal with the physical and cognitive decline of the previous generation, as well as their own discord, in “Grand Départ.”
snippet: Two brothers in France deal with the physical and cognitive decline of the previous generation, as well as their own discord, in “Grand Départ.”
lead_paragraph: Nicolas Mercier’s reassuring “Grand Départ” explores relationships painfully familiar to anyone who has dealt with an aging parent’s declining health and mental faculties. Often, in such situations, fraught connections with siblings — rivalries and unforgiven childhood slights — can be as stressful as tending to a dying loved one.

abstract: Assisted living facilities are just beginning to grapple with the questions raised by intimate relations among residents, including those with cognitive impairment.
snippet: Assisted living facilities are just beginning to grapple with the questions raised by intimate relations among residents, including those with cognitive impairment.
lead_paragraph: Trulah Goin Mills had developed dementia and couldn’t be left alone in the house, but when she and her husband, Lewis, moved into an assisted living facility in Boise, Idaho, in 2012, one lifelong quality remained intact.

abstract: With Howe in Texas recovering from a stroke and fighting the effects of dementia, the Red Wings have become traveling ambassadors for him.
snippet: With Howe in Texas recovering from a stroke and fighting the effects of dementia, the Red Wings have become traveling ambassadors for him.
lead_paragraph: OTTAWA — Gordie Howe is in Texas recovering from a stroke and fighting the effects of dementia. But wherever the Detroit Red Wings go these days, he is with them.

abstract: The death of Frank Mercado, 77, ruled a homicide by the medical examiner, highlights the hazards of nursing homes in New York, where rates of substandard care and abuse are high, according to studies.
snippet: The death of Frank Mercado, 77, ruled a homicide by the medical examiner, highlights the hazards of nursing homes in New York, where rates of substandard care and abuse are high, according to studies.
lead_paragraph: Unable to see clearly and afflicted with dementia, Frank Mercado, 77, depended completely on the care provided by the small nursing home in the Bronx where he had lived for four years. But last Monday, as Mr. Mercado cried for help, a veteran employee beat him to the ground, where he was impaled on a sharp metal protrusion from an overturned table, according to prosecutors.

abstract: Doctors need to be able to say “no” when more treatment won’t help.
snippet: Doctors need to be able to say “no” when more treatment won’t help.
lead_paragraph: MY father would have been thrilled to read “Dying in America,” a new report by the Institute of Medicine that argues that we subject dying patients to too many treatments, denying them a peaceful death. But he would have asked what took us so long. A physician from the late 1950s to the late 1990s, my dad grew increasingly angry at how patients died in this country, too often in hospitals and connected to machines and tubes he knew would not help them.

abstract: Caregiver support groups: Sometimes the best ideas are the simplest.
snippet: Caregiver support groups: Sometimes the best ideas are the simplest.
lead_paragraph: On Saturday mornings, Cyndi Mariner puts on her Nikes, grabs a hat, and heads for Shoreline Park in Mountain View, Calif. Joining a handful of other people caring for elderly parents, she walks for an hour along San Francisco Bay. The walkers watch the kayaks and sailboats on the water, notice the hummingbirds buzzing across the trail. And they talk about things like how not to scream when your loved one with dementia has asked you the same question five times in a row.

headline.main: Walking the Talk

abstract: In “Dying of the Light,” a C.I.A. operative is determined to chase down a terrorist who the agency says is already dead.
snippet: In “Dying of the Light,” a C.I.A. operative is determined to chase down a terrorist who the agency says is already dead.
lead_paragraph: Paul Schrader is credited as the writer and director of “Dying of the Light,” but that authorial attribution comes with an asterisk: The cut reaching theaters isn’t his. In protest, Mr. Schrader; his stars Nicolas Cage and Anton Yelchin; and one of his executive producers, the filmmaker Nicolas Winding Refn, have appeared online in T-shirts emblazoned with the text of a nondisparagement clause.

abstract: Sisters act; shuttle tact.
snippet: Sisters act; shuttle tact.
lead_paragraph: I am a woman with a short, boyish hairstyle. Is it unfair that I am charged more for a haircut than a man with similarly short hair? Different prices for different genders seems to me like a sexist relic from a less enlightened time. When I called local salons to find a new stylist (mine moved away), many of them balked when I said I should be charged the men’s rate because I have short hair. Many salons claim that “it has always been done that way.” This seems like a very bad excuse for an antiquated and discriminatory policy. YUKI MURATA, SANTA FE, N.M.

abstract: Brookdale Senior Living and Emeritus Corporation, in announcing the $2.8 billion merger on Thursday, said that 6.5 million people 80 years or older will live within 10 miles of a Brookdale community once the deal is completed.
snippet: Brookdale Senior Living and Emeritus Corporation, in announcing the $2.8 billion merger on Thursday, said that 6.5 million people 80 years or older will live within 10 miles of a Brookdale community once the deal is completed.
lead_paragraph: Many octogenarians will not have to travel far to find senior living housing after the merger of two of the country’s leading elder care companies.

abstract: Gustavo Dudamel is returning to Avery Fisher Hall next month to lead the Los Angeles Philharmonic in concerts featuring works by Rachmaninoff, Bjarnason, Corigliano and others.
snippet: Gustavo Dudamel is returning to Avery Fisher Hall next month to lead the Los Angeles Philharmonic in concerts featuring works by Rachmaninoff, Bjarnason, Corigliano and others.
lead_paragraph: Reviewing a concert featuring the “Infernal Dance” of Stravinsky’s “Firebird” that Gustavo Dudamel led with the Los Angeles Philharmonic last March at Avery Fisher Hall, Anthony Tommasini wrote in The New York Times that Mr. Dudamel “drew such blazing colors, slashing attacks and sheer terror from the orchestra that at the climax of the dance, some people in the hall broke into applause and shouted ‘Bravo.’ ”

abstract: Finally, a film about aging that doesn’t depress.
snippet: Finally, a film about aging that doesn’t depress.
lead_paragraph: Attention, moviegoers interested in aging who thought “The Iron Lady” was too depressing, “Nebraska” was too depressing, and “Amour” was off-the-charts depressing. I’ve got a tip for you: “Land Ho!”

abstract: A race with so much dirty politics deserves a cocktail to match: a version of the Mississippi Mudslide.
snippet: A race with so much dirty politics deserves a cocktail to match: a version of the Mississippi Mudslide.
lead_paragraph: No two ways about it: The race for the Mississippi Senate seat long held by Thad Cochran is ugly. A supporter of his challenger, Chris McDaniel, faces charges for breaking into a nursing home and photographing Mr. Cochran’s wife, who is being treated for dementia. The bitter primary race was so close on Tuesday that it is now heading to a runoff election June 24.

abstract: It’s hard to imagine a health care setting more ill suited for the elderly than today’s emergency rooms.
snippet: It’s hard to imagine a health care setting more ill suited for the elderly than today’s emergency rooms.
lead_paragraph: The elderly man lived alone in an apartment complex not far from the hospital. A younger neighbor, who’d watched him hobble down the building’s stairwell for nearly a week, insisted on taking him to the emergency room. Doctors there immediately diagnosed an infection in his painful toe and prescribed antibiotics for him to take at home.

headline.main: The Policy Lapsed, but No One Knew

abstract: Researchers found C.T.E., a disease linked to football and boxing, in a soccer player who loved to head the ball, although they said the cause was inconclusive.
snippet: Researchers found C.T.E., a disease linked to football and boxing, in a soccer player who loved to head the ball, although they said the cause was inconclusive.
lead_paragraph: Chronic traumatic encephalopathy, the degenerative brain disease linked to repeated blows to the head, has been found posthumously in a 29-year-old former soccer player, the strongest indication yet that the condition is not limited to athletes who played sports known for violent collisions, like football and boxing.

abstract: A small study found that many elderly patients turning up in one emergency room were malnourished.
snippet: A small study found that many elderly patients turning up in one emergency room were malnourished.
lead_paragraph: Many seniors who seek care in emergency departments may be malnourished, a small study by researchers at the University of North Carolina suggests. The study is among the first to attempt to document the extent of this problem.

abstract: Trisha Brown Dance Company, which is winding down, is expected to announce on Tuesday that it has raised $2.5 million toward keeping Ms. Brown’s work in the public eye.
snippet: Trisha Brown Dance Company, which is winding down, is expected to announce on Tuesday that it has raised $2.5 million toward keeping Ms. Brown’s work in the public eye.
lead_paragraph: As the Trisha Brown Dance Company nears the halfway point of a three-year farewell tour, it plans to announce on Tuesday that it has raised half of the $5 million that it is seeking to preserve Ms. Brown’s legacy through educational initiatives and occasional performances.

abstract: Jonatha Brooke talks about her mother’s descent into Alzheimer’s disease, the basis of her one-woman show, “My Mother Has 4 Noses.”
snippet: Jonatha Brooke talks about her mother’s descent into Alzheimer’s disease, the basis of her one-woman show, “My Mother Has 4 Noses.”
lead_paragraph: Outside, the sleet came down like needles, a perfect night for slipper socks and 1940s weepers on Turner Classic Movies. But no: I have tickets to “My Mother Has 4 Noses,” a one-woman musical written and performed by the singer/songwriter Jonatha Brooke about the harrowing years when she saw her mother through the final stages of Alzheimer’s disease.

headline.main: Music Born of Magical Thinking

abstract: Ms. Patterson, with her husband, Ron, created the first modern Renaissance fair in an effort “to bring history to life.”
snippet: Ms. Patterson, with her husband, Ron, created the first modern Renaissance fair in an effort “to bring history to life.”
lead_paragraph: Phyllis Patterson, who brought 16th-century Europe to Southern California in the 1960s when she helped found the first contemporary Renaissance fair, died on May 18 in a hospital in San Rafael, Calif. She was 82 and lived in a log cabin nearby, in Novato.

abstract: When an estate is parceled out in unequal shares, family members can turn on one another and no one benefits except the lawyers.
snippet: When an estate is parceled out in unequal shares, family members can turn on one another and no one benefits except the lawyers.
lead_paragraph: KATE’S father died when she was in college, but she stayed close to his side of the family. Although she moved to North Carolina after graduation, she and her three siblings returned to New Jersey a couple of times a year to visit her grandmother, aunts and cousins. She called her grandmother frequently until dementia made it impossible for them to communicate.

abstract: Writing or executing a will may mean resolving some familial issues beforehand, rather than having sibling rivalries dominate afterward.

lead_paragraph: Sheila Heen, an expert in negotiation and difficult conversations, is answering reader questions about how to resolve disputes within families and in other parts of life.

headline.main: Negotiating Conflicts, Part 5: A Tug of Wills

abstract: The guarantee is part of a revised settlement in a contentious lawsuit filed by about 5,000 retired players who accused the league of hiding the dangers of concussions from them.
snippet: The guarantee is part of a revised settlement in a contentious lawsuit filed by about 5,000 retired players who accused the league of hiding the dangers of concussions from them.
lead_paragraph: The N.F.L. has made an open-ended commitment to pay cash awards to retired players who have dementia and other conditions linked to repeated head hits, according to documents filed in the United States District Court for the Eastern District of Pennsylvania on Wednesday.

abstract: The White House conference on sports-related concussions, while a big step in the fight for awareness, came too late for many athletes.
snippet: The White House conference on sports-related concussions, while a big step in the fight for awareness, came too late for many athletes.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Not a single seat was empty in the East Room of the White House on Thursday during a conference, organized by President Obama, on the dangers of sports-related concussions.

abstract: Opinions on the Afghanistan compromise, German surveillance, fortifying the highway fund and Chicago football’s impact on the brain.
snippet: Opinions on the Afghanistan compromise, German surveillance, fortifying the highway fund and Chicago football’s impact on the brain.
lead_paragraph: “The compromise deal over Afghanistan’s bitterly contested presidential election is a big relief and a credit to all involved,” writes The New York Times editorial board. “Especially Abdullah Abdullah and Ashraf Ghani, the two candidates, and Secretary of State John Kerry, who brokered the agreement in 12 hours of intense negotiations.” The deal diverts the possibility of civil war and “offers a chance for a peaceful transition” of power after more than a decade of presidential rule by Hamid Karzai. “But it would not have been possible without President Obama’s threat to withhold aid, the billions of dollars that have propped up Afghanistan’s economy and underwritten its security forces, and without which it could well go the way of Iraq.” The board is cautiously optimistic: “Mr. Obama must be prepared, if necessary, to use that leverage again to ensure the deal is carried out.”

abstract: Some scientists have linked gluten with neurological symptoms.
snippet: Some scientists have linked gluten with neurological symptoms.
lead_paragraph: WHEN Andre H. Lagrange, a neurologist at Vanderbilt University in Nashville, saw the ominous white spots on the patient’s brain scan, he considered infection or lymphoma, a type of cancer. But tests ruled out both. Meanwhile, anti-epilepsy drugs failed to halt the man’s seizures. Stumped, Dr. Lagrange turned to something the mother of the 30-year-old man kept repeating. The fits coincided, she insisted, with spells of constipation and diarrhea.

abstract: Genetic testing of embryos raises unsettling ethical questions that trouble advocates for the disabled and have left some doctors struggling with what they should tell their patients.
snippet: Genetic testing of embryos raises unsettling ethical questions that trouble advocates for the disabled and have left some doctors struggling with what they should tell their patients.
lead_paragraph: Her first thought after she heard the news, after she screamed and made her mother and boyfriend leave the room, was that she would never have children. Amanda Baxley’s doctor had just told her, over a speakerphone in her psychiatrist’s office, that she had the gene for Gerstmann-Straussler-Scheinker disease, or GSS, which would inevitably lead to her slow and terrible death.

abstract: A couple, married for 28 years, considers an uncertain future because of the ravages of dementia.
snippet: A couple, married for 28 years, considers an uncertain future because of the ravages of dementia.
lead_paragraph: In December my wife and I moved out of our house into an independent-living apartment. Walking through the building, you might take it for a well-kept hotel, until you notice the handrails lining the hallways, the nursing assistants in the common areas and the people pushing walkers in front of them rather than pulling luggage carts behind them. The average resident is close to 80 years old.

abstract: After ordering the extradition to Germany of Johann Breyer, 89, who served as an armed guard at Auschwitz, a judge learned that the man had died hours earlier.
snippet: After ordering the extradition to Germany of Johann Breyer, 89, who served as an armed guard at Auschwitz, a judge learned that the man had died hours earlier.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In what will most likely be one of the last Nazi cases on American soil, an 89-year-old Philadelphia man who served as an armed guard at Auschwitz during World War II died Wednesday, just hours before a judge ordered him extradited to Germany in the murders of 216,000 prisoners at the notorious concentration camp.

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 8 P.M. (Fuse) PIRATE RADIO (2009) The time: Britain in the mid-1960s, when the BBC, aided by the government, kept official radio channels mostly free of rock ’n’ roll. The place: a tanker off the British coast, where rebel broadcasters (Philip Seymour Hoffman, Bill Nighy and Rhys Ifans, above at microphone) blasted the Stones, the Kinks, Jimi Hendrix and the Who over the airwaves. This angers a government minister (Kenneth Branagh) who wants to keep listeners safe with high culture and educational programming. The director of this movie, Richard Curtis, “isn’t concerned with exploring why gatekeepers might want to maintain the divide between high and popular culture,” Manohla Dargis wrote in The New York Times. “He wants to party. So he piles on the comic high jinks, lobs the jokes and cranks the splendid tunes.” Mr. Nighy can also be seen as a financially distressed British retiree lured to Jaipur, India, in John Madden’s “Best Exotic Marigold Hotel” (2012), at 4:45 on MoreMax, and as the washed-up rock star Billy Mack, angling for a comeback, in Mr. Curtis’s “Love Actually” (2003), at 8 on Showtime.

abstract: It’s associated with more happiness than you might think.
snippet: It’s associated with more happiness than you might think.
lead_paragraph: LAST week the biologist Richard Dawkins sparked controversy when, in response to a woman’s hypothetical question about whether to carry to term a child with Down syndrome, he wrote on Twitter: “Abort it and try again. It would be immoral to bring it into the world if you have the choice.”

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 6 A.M. (TCM) 24 HOURS OF HORROR Turner Classic Movies kicks off its annual fright fest with “London After Midnight” (1927), Tod Browning’s lost masterpiece starring Lon Chaney as a vampire, reconstructed entirely from stills and backed by a new score by the composer Robert Israel. Other highlights include “Mark of the Vampire” (1935), Browning’s talkie remake of “London After Midnight,” this time starring Bela Lugosi, at 7; “Cat People” (1942), with Simone Simon as a Serbian fashion designer who turns into a panther when aroused, at 11; Francis Ford Coppola’s “Dementia” (1963), at 3:15; Roman Polanski’s “Repulsion” (1965), starring Catherine Deneuve as an introverted Belgian manicurist living in London who is increasingly tormented by sexuality, at 6:15; “Night of the Living Dead” (1968), George A. Romero’s zombie classic, at 8; “House of Wax” (1953), with Vincent Price in his first major horror role, as a sinister sculptor, at 11:45; and Tobe Hooper’s “Poltergeist” (1982), at 1:30 a.m.

abstract: Judge Anita B. Brody said she wants more proof that the $765 million in a proposed settlement for retired N.F.L. players will last 65 years.

lead_paragraph: When the N.F.L. and the lawyers for the 4,500 retirees who sued the league said in August that they had reached a $765 million deal to end their dispute, there was hope on all sides that a resolution to the standoff would come soon.

abstract: In addition to his concert and recording career, Mr. Frank was also an influential teacher of generations of pianists.
snippet: In addition to his concert and recording career, Mr. Frank was also an influential teacher of generations of pianists.
lead_paragraph: The American pianist Claude Frank, widely admired for his insightful, sensitive performances of the solo and chamber works of the Germanic masters, and an influential teacher to generations of pianists, died on Saturday at his home in Manhattan, three days after turning 89.

headline.main: Claude Frank, Pianist Admired for Performing Beethoven, Dies at 89
headline.print_headline: Claude Frank, Pianist, Is Dead at 89

abstract: A $1.2 million donation from Steve Tisch, an owner of the N.F.L. team, will pay to have trainers or emergency medical technicians at all contact practices for New York City’s public high schools.
snippet: A $1.2 million donation from Steve Tisch, an owner of the N.F.L. team, will pay to have trainers or emergency medical technicians at all contact practices for New York City’s public high schools.
lead_paragraph: For decades, a powerfully built football player tottering on his feet was considered just a part of the game. But increasingly, potential signals of a head injury, like that stagger, are considered dangerous warning signs that should be scouted for on every level of the sport.

abstract: “Girlfriends’ Guide to Divorce,” the first scripted series for Bravo, taps into the separations of the rich and near-famous and all the attendant rituals.
snippet: “Girlfriends’ Guide to Divorce,” the first scripted series for Bravo, taps into the separations of the rich and near-famous and all the attendant rituals.
lead_paragraph: There are businesses that bet on breakups. Patricia Cohen, an ex-wife of Steven A. Cohen, the hedge fund billionaire, recently received an infusion of cash, known as litigation financing, from a California company, Balance Point Divorce Funding, to continue her lawsuit against her former husband.

abstract: While the drug, crenezumab, did not slow progression of the disease over all, at the highest doses it seemed to delay a decline in mental ability in patients with mild Alzheimer’s.
snippet: While the drug, crenezumab, did not slow progression of the disease over all, at the highest doses it seemed to delay a decline in mental ability in patients with mild Alzheimer’s.
lead_paragraph: Roche, the pharmaceutical company, on Wednesday reported mixed results in its latest trial of an Alzheimer’s drug. It said that while the drug did not slow progression of the disease over all, at the highest doses it did seem to delay a decline in mental ability in patients with mild cases of Alzheimer’s.
headline.main: Roche Reports Mixed Results in Trial of an Alzheimer’s Drug
headline.print_headline: Mixed Results for Roche in Alzheimer’s Drug Trial

abstract: Flames swept through the Mariner’s Cove Motor Inn in Pleasant Point Beach, N.J., which had been used to shelter people who lost their homes in Hurricane Sandy.
snippet: Flames swept through the Mariner’s Cove Motor Inn in Pleasant Point Beach, N.J., which had been used to shelter people who lost their homes in Hurricane Sandy.
lead_paragraph: A fire swept through a motel at Point Pleasant Beach on the Jersey Shore just before dawn on Friday, killing four people and injuring eight others.

abstract: Television highlights.
snippet: Television highlights.
lead_paragraph: 11:35 A.M. (Starz Cinema) A SEPARATION (2011) In this Oscar winner for best foreign-language film, a couple (Leila Hatami, above, and Peyman Moadi) must decide whether to leave Iran for the sake of their daughter or stay to care for a parent with dementia. Either option could end their marriage. “It is a rigorously honest movie about the difficulties of being honest, a film that tries to be truthful about the slipperiness of truth,” A. O. Scott wrote in The New York Times about this drama, written and directed by Asghar Farhadi and starring his daughter, Sarina, as the couple’s child. “It also sketches a portrait — perhaps an unnervingly familiar picture for American audiences — of a society divided by sex, generation, religion and class.”

abstract: Alzheimer’s is deadly, costly and finally getting the blunt discussion it needs.

lead_paragraph: My maternal grandmother lives in my memory as two distinct images. Two distinct people, really.

headline.main: Confronting an Ugly Killer
headline.print_headline: Confronting an Ugly Killer

abstract: In light of recent discoveries about concussions, a football fan questions his support.
snippet: In light of recent discoveries about concussions, a football fan questions his support.
lead_paragraph: I’ve recently begun to question my support for the N.F.L. I suspect that the recent discoveries about concussions and the prevalence of early-onset dementia among players are just the tip of the iceberg. Is it unethical to support a league that seems to know it is detrimental to the health of its participants? And if so, what should my response be? Don’t go to games? Don’t buy merchandise? Don’t watch on television? Start actively opposing the N.F.L.? Write letters? DARREN WILLIAMS, DALLAS

abstract: An attempt to save a marriage proves fatal.
snippet: An attempt to save a marriage proves fatal.
lead_paragraph: Punishment and penance for marital infidelity can take many forms, and on the face of it, the means by which a painter named Gus (short for Augusta) Edelman, the narrator of Robin Black’s first novel, is paying for the sin of cheating on her husband — a retreat to an isolated house in the country — has a certain amount of appeal, at least to creative types like them. It’s Yaddo with no company but their own.

headline.print_headline: Grudge Match

abstract: A series of fires in a New England town exposes tensions between summer and year-round residents.
snippet: A series of fires in a New England town exposes tensions between summer and year-round residents.
lead_paragraph: In the middle of the night, a jet-lagged woman, unable to sleep, goes for a walk along a country road in the New England town where her family has summered for generations. Frankie Rowley, newly returned from years of relief work in Africa, is certainly lost in the middle of her life’s journey, and in a dark night, if not precisely in a dark wood. Unsure of her place in the world, unsure whether she has a place in the world, Frankie has come to Pomeroy, N.H., for a life-reassessment disguised as a visit to her parents, who have decided to live full time in their summer house following her father’s retirement from teaching. It’s only after a car passes Frankie on the road, its headlights sweeping past in a disorienting arc, that she realizes the smell of smoke has been in the air for some time.

abstract: Slaughter in the Middle East cannot be an alibi for Israel to avoid self-scrutiny.
snippet: Slaughter in the Middle East cannot be an alibi for Israel to avoid self-scrutiny.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — Attending services at a Reform synagogue during the High Holy Days in London I heard sermons of great worthiness from British rabbis. One was about Alzheimer’s and dementia among the elderly and the need to honor the “fragment of the divine in everyone.” Another was about changes to the prayer book, including the dropping of the term “Lord,” with its male overtones.

abstract: A United States District Court judge heard hours of arguments about the fairness of the deal between the N.F.L. and its former players.
snippet: A United States District Court judge heard hours of arguments about the fairness of the deal between the N.F.L. and its former players.
lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — After hundreds of court filings over the past 16 months, opponents of the preliminary settlement between the N.F.L. and the 5,000 former players who sued the league for hiding the dangers of concussions urged a federal judge on Wednesday to alter key parts of the deal.

abstract: A member of the “aging industrial complex” starts a campaign against ageism.
snippet: A member of the “aging industrial complex” starts a campaign against ageism.
lead_paragraph: When we last checked in with Alice Fisher, Hurricane Sandy had forced her ailing 90-year-old parents out of their ruined co-op apartment in Long Beach, N.Y., where they had expected — with the enthusiastic approval of their two daughters — to live out their days.
headline.main: Stealing a Page From the Boomers’ Playbook

abstract: Mr. Kasem, the longtime host of “American Top 40,” was known for his homey sentiment and an optimism that ran headlong into the prevailing spirit of rebellion in 1970s music culture.
snippet: Mr. Kasem, the longtime host of “American Top 40,” was known for his homey sentiment and an optimism that ran headlong into the prevailing spirit of rebellion in 1970s music culture.
lead_paragraph: Casey Kasem, a disc jockey who never claimed to love rock ’n’ roll but who built a long and lucrative career from it, creating and hosting one of radio’s most popular syndicated pop music shows, “American Top 40,” died on Sunday in a hospital in Gig Harbor, Wash. He was 82.
headline.main: Casey Kasem, Wholesome Voice of Pop Radio, Dies at 82
headline.print_headline: Casey Kasem, 82, Homey Radio Voice of America’s Top 40 Pop Songs, Dies

abstract: Transition “coaches” help ease the transfer from hospital to home.
snippet: Transition “coaches” help ease the transfer from hospital to home.
lead_paragraph: The transitions coach ducks into your mother’s hospital room for a brief introduction before she’s discharged. The coach explains that her job is to help keep patients safe at home and asks if she can call to set up a home visit.
headline.main: Clearing the Path Home

abstract: The primary fight between Senator Thad Cochran and his Tea Party challenger descended into voter fraud accusations, and a tragic note was introduced when a Tea Party leader committed suicide.
snippet: The primary fight between Senator Thad Cochran and his Tea Party challenger descended into voter fraud accusations, and a tragic note was introduced when a Tea Party leader committed suicide.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The long and bitter Republican primary fight between Senator Thad Cochran and his Tea Party challenger descended into accusations of voter fraud on Friday, with the defeated candidate, State Senator Chris McDaniel, making clear he would not accept the results anytime soon.

abstract: The nonfiction nominees for the 2014 National Book Award include Roz Chast’s “Can’t We Talk About Something More Pleasant?” and John Lahr’s biography of Tennessee Williams.
snippet: The nonfiction nominees for the 2014 National Book Award include Roz Chast’s “Can’t We Talk About Something More Pleasant?” and John Lahr’s biography of Tennessee Williams.
lead_paragraph: The National Book Award nominees for the 2014 nonfiction prize were announced on Wednesday. The 10 nominated works include two books about World War II, a coming book from Walter Isaacson about technological innovation and, for the first time in the nonfiction category, a graphic memoir, from the New Yorker cartoonist Roz Chast.

abstract: Annette O’Toole takes the lead in a production of Wendy Wasserstein’s “Third,” staged at Two River Theater in Red Bank.
snippet: Annette O’Toole takes the lead in a production of Wendy Wasserstein’s “Third,” staged at Two River Theater in Red Bank.
lead_paragraph: Wendy Wasserstein is best remembered for writing thoughtful, witty plays about smart women of her baby boom generation.

abstract: The more physically active you are in your 20s, the better your thinking tends to be when you reach middle age, according to a large-scale new study. But it’s never too late to improve the health of your brain.
snippet: The more physically active you are in your 20s, the better your thinking tends to be when you reach middle age, according to a large-scale new study. But it’s never too late to improve the health of your brain.
lead_paragraph: The more physically active you are at age 25, the better your thinking tends to be when you reach middle age, according to a large-scale new study. Encouragingly, the findings also suggest that if you negligently neglected to exercise when young, you can start now and still improve the health of your brain.

abstract: Dr. Bernt Nesje, 67, has two guidelines for taking on patients: They must live in or around Greenwich Village, and they must be older than he is.
snippet: Dr. Bernt Nesje, 67, has two guidelines for taking on patients: They must live in or around Greenwich Village, and they must be older than he is.
lead_paragraph: Dr. Bernt Nesje, 67, says he has two guidelines for taking on patients: They must live in or around Greenwich Village, “and they have to be older than me.”

abstract: Spurred by the momentum the issue has gained in the United States, Parliament is examining a tightening of the rules governing the response to sports-related concussions.
snippet: Spurred by the momentum the issue has gained in the United States, Parliament is examining a tightening of the rules governing the response to sports-related concussions.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — Spurred by the momentum the issue has gained in the United States, British lawmakers have started their own campaign to highlight the incidence of serious head injuries in sports, calling for a tightening of the rules governing the way that players, coaches, team doctors, professional leagues and parents respond to sports-related concussions.
headline.main: British Lawmakers Intensify Focus on Head Injuries
headline.print_headline: British Lawmakers Intensify Focus on Head Injuries

abstract: The National Football League and the United States military should be more honest about the high risks associated with their workplaces, Tony Schwartz writes in his Life@Work column.
snippet: The National Football League and the United States military should be more honest about the high risks associated with their workplaces, Tony Schwartz writes in his Life@Work column.
lead_paragraph: I spend my days trying to make workplaces more humane, but recently I’ve been thinking a lot about why people would voluntarily choose to work in one that is dangerous, debilitating and often lethal. Actually, I have two in mind.

headline.main: Football, War and the Workplace

abstract: In ‘Annapurna,’ by Sharr White, a middle-aged American named Ulysses is frying sausages in his trailer and sounding like a cowboy, not a former English professor.
snippet: In ‘Annapurna,’ by Sharr White, a middle-aged American named Ulysses is frying sausages in his trailer and sounding like a cowboy, not a former English professor.
lead_paragraph: Ulysses is one major oddball. Not the hero of “The Odyssey,” in this case, or James Joyce’s novel, but the wreck of a middle-aged American man portrayed in Sharr White’s “Annapurna,” which is the strong and poignant opening production of Theaterworks Hartford’s 2014-15 season.

abstract: New York is one of at least 26 states rolling out managed long-term care programs under Medicaid, but the widely praised version in Tennessee has had problems.
snippet: New York is one of at least 26 states rolling out managed long-term care programs under Medicaid, but the widely praised version in Tennessee has had problems.
lead_paragraph: NASHVILLE — Even as public attention is focused on the Affordable Care Act, another health care overhaul is underway in many states: an ambitious effort to restrain the ballooning Medicaid cost of long-term care as people live longer and survive more disabling conditions.

abstract: Should patients be held responsible for not showing up for follow-up tests and procedures? Does the medical profession have an ethical and legal duty to try to track down the individuals?
snippet: Should patients be held responsible for not showing up for follow-up tests and procedures? Does the medical profession have an ethical and legal duty to try to track down the individuals?
lead_paragraph: Several years ago, I saw a woman with unexpectedly high blood pressure. Her readings were as high as 140/110, way above the normal value of 120/80. Though she was otherwise healthy, she was at risk of a stroke.

abstract: I welcomed the idea of touring a new hospice facility to confront my fears of pain while dying, writes Susan Gubar in her continuing “Living With Cancer” series.
snippet: I welcomed the idea of touring a new hospice facility to confront my fears of pain while dying, writes Susan Gubar in her continuing “Living With Cancer” series.
lead_paragraph: Before the visit, I had been split in two not by fear of death but by dread of dying — in anxiety, dementia, but mostly in pain from recurrent ovarian cancer.

abstract: The primary election season has been packed with important political lessons for us all. Let’s count them up!
snippet: The primary election season has been packed with important political lessons for us all. Let’s count them up!
lead_paragraph: We’ve learned so much this election season. True, almost nobody has noticed yet that there’s been voting. But trust me, the lessons are mounting.

abstract: As their children grow older and the spy game gets more intense, Elizabeth and Philip struggle to balance parenting and spying.
snippet: As their children grow older and the spy game gets more intense, Elizabeth and Philip struggle to balance parenting and spying.
lead_paragraph: When we last saw them, in Episode 2, Elizabeth and Philip were in mourning. Their friends – and let’s be clear, their only friends – Emmett and Leanne, were murdered, along with the couple’s teenage daughter, Amelia.

abstract: Physicians too often fail to address the needs of caregivers, a clinical review finds.
snippet: Physicians too often fail to address the needs of caregivers, a clinical review finds.
lead_paragraph: Not once in the years I cared for my mother did any of her physicians ask me how I was doing. When was the last time I saw my own physician? Was I eating properly? Sleeping enough? Depressed?
headline.main: Seeing the ‘Invisible Patient’

abstract: Thieves lure older victims with charity solicitations or promises of merchandise and prizes, resulting in huge losses of money, trust and confidence.
snippet: Thieves lure older victims with charity solicitations or promises of merchandise and prizes, resulting in huge losses of money, trust and confidence.
lead_paragraph: Barely a week passes in this house without one of us picking up the phone to an automated call offering my parents a free medical alert system. Of course, it is not free, but rather a well-known fraud trying to get their credit card information either for a donation, shipping or some additional emergency service.

abstract: Given the culture of the National Football League, which grooves on manliness, Cowboys quarterback Tony Romo is an odds-on bet to trot out onto the field this Sunday against the Jacksonville Jaguars, who are 1-8.
snippet: Given the culture of the National Football League, which grooves on manliness, Cowboys quarterback Tony Romo is an odds-on bet to trot out onto the field this Sunday against the Jacksonville Jaguars, who are 1-8.
lead_paragraph: The Circus Maximus known as the National Football League alighted in London for a game between the Dallas Cowboys and the Jacksonville Jaguars. The league’s many fascinations will be on display: its wonderful athleticism, its stupendous television ratings, and its blithe disregard for the safety of its most valuable commodities, the players.

abstract: A study casts doubt on the life sentence, as the population of aging inmates continues to swell, along with the cost of keeping them locked up.
snippet: A study casts doubt on the life sentence, as the population of aging inmates continues to swell, along with the cost of keeping them locked up.
lead_paragraph: In a wheelchair, the 86-year-old man was getting ready for a parole board hearing to see if he might leave New York’s prison system after 33 years behind bars. It was essential that he express remorse for his crime. “He asked me to read the sentencing minutes,” said Elizabeth Gaynes, the director of the Osborne Association, an inmate advocacy organization. “He wasn’t sure he could remember his crime well enough, and was worried that he would sound like he wasn’t taking responsibility for it.”

abstract: Chris McDaniel, a Tea Party favorite, has a solid chance to oust Senator Thad Cochran, but he’ll need a big turnout from populist voters.
snippet: Chris McDaniel, a Tea Party favorite, has a solid chance to oust Senator Thad Cochran, but he’ll need a big turnout from populist voters.
lead_paragraph: For all of the Tea Party’s struggles this year, it has a real chance to unseat an incumbent Republican in the Mississippi Republican primary Tuesday. Thad Cochran, the first Republican senator from Mississippi since Reconstruction, is facing a strong challenge from Chris McDaniel, a Tea Party-backed state senator.

abstract: The National Institutes of Health, 10 drug companies and seven nonprofits will collaborate to speed the development of treatments for Alzheimer’s, Type 2 diabetes, rheumatoid arthritis and lupus.
snippet: The National Institutes of Health, 10 drug companies and seven nonprofits will collaborate to speed the development of treatments for Alzheimer’s, Type 2 diabetes, rheumatoid arthritis and lupus.
lead_paragraph: The National Institutes of Health, 10 large drug companies and seven nonprofit organizations announced  an unconventional partnership on Tuesday intended to speed up development of drugs to treat Alzheimer’s disease, Type 2 diabetes, rheumatoid arthritis and lupus.

abstract: The N.F.L. is more popular — and more profitable — than ever. But its coming settlement over brain injuries could lay the groundwork that pushes the sport to the margins of American culture.
snippet: The N.F.L. is more popular — and more profitable — than ever. But its coming settlement over brain injuries could lay the groundwork that pushes the sport to the margins of American culture.
lead_paragraph: There are 1.27 million lawyers in the United States, one for about every 300 Americans — about 400,000 more of them than there are doctors. Their work is rarely glamorous, and especially for those just starting out in the profession, it can be grinding and repetitive. Jason Luckasevic, hired out of law school in 2000 by a firm in Pittsburgh, passed the bar exam on his first try and was quickly sworn in to practice. The ceremony, such as it was, took place on a Thursday in a clerk’s office, rather than in a courtroom in front of family and friends, because his bosses needed him to get started. The following Monday morning, he drove to Johnstown, about 90 minutes away, where he spent the day taking depositions from former employees of an enormous steel plant that had exposed them to asbestos. Late that afternoon, he climbed back into his Honda Civic and headed home. He repeated this routine for the next six months, five days a week, racking up some 400 depositions and about 20,000 miles on the road.

abstract: Is Leo Sharp a senile day-lily farmer who was taken advantage of by drug smugglers? Or did he know exactly what he was getting into?
snippet: Is Leo Sharp a senile day-lily farmer who was taken advantage of by drug smugglers? Or did he know exactly what he was getting into?
lead_paragraph: The Lincoln pickup truck with Iowa plates was hurtling down Interstate 94, headed for Detroit. A dozen D.E.A. officers in unmarked cars were scattered along a 70-mile stretch, from Kalamazoo to Jackson, Mich. From on-ramps and overpasses, they watched traffic flash by as they tried to spot the truck. They believed it was carrying a major shipment of cocaine.

abstract: Every family seems to have one caregiver who has to look out for parents as they age; some also have out-of-state siblings who do not.
snippet: Every family seems to have one caregiver who has to look out for parents as they age; some also have out-of-state siblings who do not.
lead_paragraph: A friend of mine, Sarah, recently put her mother, who has early-stage dementia, into a nursing home in the town where she lives. Moving her mother out of the family home after 40 years was anything but easy, but neither was driving an hour each way to check on her well-being several times a week.

abstract: The Los Angeles Philharmonic, led by Gustavo Dudamel, arrived at Avery Fisher Hall for concerts featuring works from Brahms, John Corigliano and others.
snippet: The Los Angeles Philharmonic, led by Gustavo Dudamel, arrived at Avery Fisher Hall for concerts featuring works from Brahms, John Corigliano and others.
lead_paragraph: While many American orchestras are grappling with financial challenges and discontent among players, the Los Angeles Philharmonic looks to be a solid success story. Relations between management and musicians seem very positive. A four-year contract signed last fall included slight annual raises in the salaries of the players. Walt Disney Concert Hall, the coolest symphonic performance space in America, remains a big draw. Most important, the charismatic conductor Gustavo Dudamel, 33, now in his fifth season as music director, continues to galvanize audiences in the Los Angeles area while heading the orchestra’s impressive community outreach and education efforts.

abstract: In 55 bouts, Terrell had 21 knockouts and a record of 46-9. He briefly shared the heavyweight championship with Muhammad Ali.
snippet: In 55 bouts, Terrell had 21 knockouts and a record of 46-9. He briefly shared the heavyweight championship with Muhammad Ali.
lead_paragraph: Ernie Terrell, who briefly shared the heavyweight championship with the fighter then widely known as Cassius Clay and who later, after refusing to acknowledge that Clay had taken the Muslim name Muhammad Ali, was battered by him in a 15-round grudge match, died on Tuesday in Chicago. He was 75.

abstract: Companies should disclose the information they sell about us.
snippet: Companies should disclose the information they sell about us.
lead_paragraph: BALTIMORE — THE reputation business is exploding. Having eroded privacy for decades, shady, poorly regulated data miners, brokers and resellers have now taken creepy classification to a whole new level. They have created lists of victims of sexual assault, and lists of people with sexually transmitted diseases. Lists of people who have Alzheimer’s, dementia and AIDS. Lists of the impotent and the depressed.

abstract: Every generation has its defining “King Lear,” and I am sure that this is ours.
snippet: Every generation has its defining “King Lear,” and I am sure that this is ours.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — “Shakespeare,” wrote the American philosopher Allan Bloom, “was an eminently political author.” On this matter, at least, the great controversialist was correct: As Mr. Bloom wrote 50 years ago in “Shakespeare’s Politics,” there was a time when “the political man seemed to be the most interesting theme of poetry.”

abstract: Cheers from St. Mildred and her sisters, for the Church of England.
snippet: Cheers from St. Mildred and her sisters, for the Church of England.
lead_paragraph: SANDWICH, England — LAST Tuesday, on the front page of The Daily Telegraph of London, which I buy like thousands of other dementia-fearers because of the kindly crossword, I saw the face of a young woman at the General Synod at York with a bright teardrop sliding down her cheek. I thought, Oh dear! More misery. Newspapers now are only frigates of misery.

abstract: In Tom Bouman’s “Dry Bones in the Valley,” an elderly recluse finds a stranger dead on his property in northeastern Pennsylvania.
snippet: In Tom Bouman’s “Dry Bones in the Valley,” an elderly recluse finds a stranger dead on his property in northeastern Pennsylvania.
lead_paragraph: Some stories are so sad, you want them to have the comfort of a gentle storytelling voice. Tom Bouman extends that kindness in DRY BONES IN THE VALLEY (Norton, $24.95), his beautifully written first novel set in the mountainous region of northeastern Pennsylvania that sits atop the Marcellus Shale, a vast geological treasure, prized and exploited for its natural gas resources. With neighbors feuding over whether to lease drilling rights to companies accused of poisoning the environment, it’s no wonder that a crazy old recluse like Aubrey Dunigan would be testy with anyone he finds hanging around his decrepit farm. But these hills are also overrun with meth cookers, dope dealers and Mexican drug cartels. So just because a stranger is found dead on his property doesn’t make poor old Aubrey a murderer.

abstract: It was tough to persuade women to begin getting regular mammograms. Decades later, it’s tough getting older women to stop.
snippet: It was tough to persuade women to begin getting regular mammograms. Decades later, it’s tough getting older women to stop.
lead_paragraph: A sad fact: None of the eight major clinical trials looking at whether regular mammograms reduce a woman’s risk of dying from breast cancer has included women over age 75.

abstract: While I was worrying about giving my 17-year-old son the keys to the family car, my friend was worrying about how to take them away from her mother, who was already showing early signs of mental confusion.
snippet: While I was worrying about giving my 17-year-old son the keys to the family car, my friend was worrying about how to take them away from her mother, who was already showing early signs of mental confusion.
lead_paragraph: Though I am the mother of three children, I have always had a lot of childless friends. Perhaps what I enjoy most about them — beyond the fact that they never need to find a sitter to meet me for a drink — is that the subject of parenting rarely comes up. With my fellow mommy friends, we discuss little else, and almost always over coffee.

abstract: When someone is spending $3,500 or more a month for assisted living, are there fewer activities the resident can’t manage?
snippet: When someone is spending $3,500 or more a month for assisted living, are there fewer activities the resident can’t manage?
lead_paragraph: “Unmet needs,” a term gerontologists use, refers to care or help you require but don’t get. If, when you’re elderly or disabled, you aren’t able to shop or cook, you lack the strength to go outside, you can’t keep track of your bank account or your medications — and no one assists you with those functions — you have unmet needs.
headline.main: Unmet Needs Continue to Pile Up

abstract: Becoming physically active in middle age, even if someone has been sedentary for years, substantially reduces the likelihood that he or she will become seriously ill or physically disabled in retirement, new research shows.
snippet: Becoming physically active in middle age, even if someone has been sedentary for years, substantially reduces the likelihood that he or she will become seriously ill or physically disabled in retirement, new research shows.
lead_paragraph: Offering hope and encouragement to the many adults who have somehow neglected to exercise for the past few decades, a new study suggests that becoming physically active in middle age, even if someone has been sedentary for years, substantially reduces the likelihood that he or she will become seriously ill or physically disabled in retirement.

abstract: Mississippi politics has always had a rough edge, but this year’s campaign to unseat Senator Thad Cochran has become the nastiest Republican primary in the nation.
snippet: Mississippi politics has always had a rough edge, but this year’s campaign to unseat Senator Thad Cochran has become the nastiest Republican primary in the nation.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The feud between the Republican establishment and the Tea Party has engendered more whimpers than war cries so far. The notable exception is in Mississippi, where the campaign to unseat Senator Thad Cochran has become the nastiest, and most personal, in the nation.
