abstract: Fast-food joints provide the elderly with a cosmopolitan alternative to senior centers.
snippet: Fast-food joints provide the elderly with a cosmopolitan alternative to senior centers.
lead_paragraph: THERE’S an old Italian saying, “A tavola non si invecchia,” which means: At the table, you don’t grow old. All of us, of whatever age, need to socialize in public places to feel connected and alive.

abstract: Now that my father is an octogenarian, we are noticing how few filters seem to strain his words, particularly when it comes to being politically correct.
snippet: Now that my father is an octogenarian, we are noticing how few filters seem to strain his words, particularly when it comes to being politically correct.
lead_paragraph: The holiday season makes me nervous. This is the time of year, after all, that our multigenerational family socializes together the most in our shared home.

lead_paragraph: As genres go, the sports biography plays by established rules. More often than not the young hero, toiling in obscurity, is suddenly recognized for his or her formidable talents. So begins the stirring journey to fame.

abstract: Addressing a need to blow off steam, issues with a neighbor, friendly reminders and unwanted comedy routines.
snippet: Addressing a need to blow off steam, issues with a neighbor, friendly reminders and unwanted comedy routines.
lead_paragraph: I was in a store today, and two people were served before me — out of turn. It happened so quickly, I didn’t say anything; they were already in the middle of their orders. When I got back to my car, I told my husband how annoyed I was. He said, “Maybe you should speak up for yourself.” This made me doubly annoyed, and I lost my temper with him. I’ve asked him many times not to give me advice unless I ask for it. Now I’m asking for yours.

headline.main: The Venting Process
headline.print_headline: The Venting Process

abstract: Why do we have to rest? Meet your brain’s janitorial staff.
snippet: Why do we have to rest? Meet your brain’s janitorial staff.
lead_paragraph: SLEEP seems like a perfectly fine waste of time. Why would our bodies evolve to spend close to one-third of our lives completely out of it, when we could instead be doing something useful or exciting? Something that would, as an added bonus, be less likely to get us killed back when we were sleeping on the savanna?

abstract: Amy Poehler’s new book, “Yes Please,” includes backstage “Saturday Night Live” stories, lists, old photos and guest essays from both her parents.
snippet: Amy Poehler’s new book, “Yes Please,” includes backstage “Saturday Night Live” stories, lists, old photos and guest essays from both her parents.
lead_paragraph: Amy Poehler’s memoirish book is titled “Yes Please,” as in Bring it on, but its tone is more “No, Really, Make This Stop,” as in Get me out of here.

headline.print_headline: ‘S.N.L.’ Memories, and a Need for Sleep

abstract: It can take 20 years for complications from diabetes to become apparent, so identifying those at risk and altering their habits could delay onset of the disease.
snippet: It can take 20 years for complications from diabetes to become apparent, so identifying those at risk and altering their habits could delay onset of the disease.
lead_paragraph: After a routine test of her blood sugar eight years ago, Randi Sue Baker, a seriously overweight 64-year-old, learned that Type 2 diabetes was bearing down.

abstract: Two new studies suggest that atrial fibrillation may be the unrecognized cause of many strokes, and that patients should be monitored for a month to find out.
snippet: Two new studies suggest that atrial fibrillation may be the unrecognized cause of many strokes, and that patients should be monitored for a month to find out.
lead_paragraph: More than a half-million Americans every year have an ischemic stroke, the most common form, which disrupts blood flow to the brain. And at least a quarter of these cases have no apparent underlying cause.

abstract: The N.F.L. is increasingly being forced to confront how to make football safer, essentially worrying the same audience that it is seeking to assure.
snippet: The N.F.L. is increasingly being forced to confront how to make football safer, essentially worrying the same audience that it is seeking to assure.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — In 2009, Roger Goodell, the commissioner of the N.F.L., was skewered by lawmakers on Capitol Hill for denying the severity of concussions and failing to do more to help retired players with brain injuries.

abstract: I found I was not alone with the guilty secret of having wished my aged mother dead.
snippet: I found I was not alone with the guilty secret of having wished my aged mother dead.
lead_paragraph: TOKYO — It was the mad, busy time just before New Year’s, the most auspicious holiday of the year, when the hospital called to tell me that my mother had just been brought in by ambulance. She had slipped on the sidewalk and broken her shoulder and hip.

abstract: Friends said Robert De Carlo’s life seemed to spiral down about four years ago when he was hit by a car and then became addicted to prescription painkillers.
snippet: Friends said Robert De Carlo’s life seemed to spiral down about four years ago when he was hit by a car and then became addicted to prescription painkillers.
lead_paragraph: The lawyer for a drug addict charged with crashing a stolen minivan into a family in Brooklyn, killing a 12-year-old girl and injuring her sister and mother, detailed on Friday how he brokered his client’s surrender as details about the suspect’s trail of recent arrests came into focus.

abstract: No matter how much attention will be shifted to the Mississippi runoff election, the intractable inertia of the typical voter will play a big role.
snippet: No matter how much attention will be shifted to the Mississippi runoff election, the intractable inertia of the typical voter will play a big role.
lead_paragraph: In winning his state senate seat in 2007, Chris McDaniel drew just over 10,000 votes. In winning a sixth United States Senate term a year later, Thad Cochran drew 766,000.

abstract: The Uruguayan-born biochemist started more than a dozen companies and had a role in the development of the birth control pill, the nicotine patch and the DNA chip.
snippet: The Uruguayan-born biochemist started more than a dozen companies and had a role in the development of the birth control pill, the nicotine patch and the DNA chip.
lead_paragraph: Alejandro Zaffaroni, a prolific biotechnology entrepreneur and Silicon Valley legend who played a significant role in the development of the birth control pill, the nicotine patch, the DNA chip and corticosteroids, died on Saturday at his home in Atherton, Calif. He was 91.

abstract: The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services acknowledged that its five-star rating system needed work, given that it relies heavily on self-reporting.
snippet: The Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services acknowledged that its five-star rating system needed work, given that it relies heavily on self-reporting.
lead_paragraph: The federal government on Monday announced substantial changes to the government’s five-star rating program for nursing homes, a widely used consumer tool that has been criticized for its reliance on self-reported, unverified data.

abstract: The National Book Foundation announced the finalists for the 2014 National Book Awards in poetry, young adult literature, nonfiction and fiction on Wednesday morning.
snippet: The National Book Foundation announced the finalists for the 2014 National Book Awards in poetry, young adult literature, nonfiction and fiction on Wednesday morning.
lead_paragraph: The National Book Foundation announced finalists for the 2014 National Book Awards in poetry, young adult literature, nonfiction and fiction on Wednesday morning. The winners will be recognized at a ceremony on Nov. 19, headlined by Daniel Handler, better known as Lemony Snicket. The five finalists in each category are:
headline.main: Shortlists for National Book Awards Announced
headline.print_headline: National Book Award Finalists Are Chosen

abstract: Be an ‘educated customer’ if the needs of an aging relative or friends become too difficult to handle at home.
snippet: Be an ‘educated customer’ if the needs of an aging relative or friends become too difficult to handle at home.
lead_paragraph: Nobody looks forward to spending their final years in a nursing home, yet 1.4 million Americans are living in this often-feared institutional setting.

abstract: Some critics have called for a boycott of the league in light of the Ray Rice and Adrian Peterson abuse scandals. But who is ultimately responsible for change — the league, its sponsors or viewers like you?
snippet: Some critics have called for a boycott of the league in light of the Ray Rice and Adrian Peterson abuse scandals. But who is ultimately responsible for change — the league, its sponsors or viewers like you?
lead_paragraph: “Are you a decent person? Do you regard yourself as having a moral compass? Do you try to lead your everyday life in accordance with some basic ethical precepts, such as not countenancing brutality, greed and deception?” If so, Michael Tracey at Vice says “then please, for God’s sake, don’t watch the N.F.L.”

headline.main: Tactic in Alzheimer’s Fight May Be Safe, Study Finds
headline.print_headline: Tactic in Alzheimer’s Fight May Be Safe, Study Finds

abstract: The factors that improve your chances of avoiding the Type 2 variety of the disease are unmistakable: weight loss and exercise.
snippet: The factors that improve your chances of avoiding the Type 2 variety of the disease are unmistakable: weight loss and exercise.
lead_paragraph: This year, nearly two million American adults and more than 5,000 children and adolescents will learn they have a potentially devastating, life-shortening, yet largely preventable disease: Type 2 diabetes. They will join 29.1 million Americans who already have diabetes.

abstract: In “Boy on Ice,” John Branch examines the death of the N.H.L. player Derek Boogaard and the role that hockey’s culture of violence may have played.
snippet: In “Boy on Ice,” John Branch examines the death of the N.H.L. player Derek Boogaard and the role that hockey’s culture of violence may have played.
lead_paragraph: Over the course of little more than three months in 2011, three National Hockey League “enforcers” — players whose primary job it is to fight — died by their own hand. Rick Rypien of the Winnipeg Jets and Wade Belak, recently retired from the Nashville Predators, committed suicide. Derek Boogaard, who played for the Minnesota Wild and New York Rangers, killed himself with an accidental overdose of alcohol and prescription painkillers.

abstract: Hospices are discharging increasing numbers of patients before they die.
snippet: Hospices are discharging increasing numbers of patients before they die.
lead_paragraph: It didn’t come as a complete surprise when a Pennsylvania hospice told Phyllis Fine’s family last year that she was no longer eligible to receive care.
headline.main: Bounced From Hospice

abstract: Has our passion for football made us blind to the sport’s dark side?
snippet: Has our passion for football made us blind to the sport’s dark side?
lead_paragraph: “The libertine,” wrote Simone de Beauvoir, “in hurting the object that serves him, ‘tastes all the pleasures which a vigorous individual feels in making full use of his strength; he dominates, he is a tyrant.’ ” She was quoting, indirectly and then directly, the Marquis de Sade.

abstract: The New Yorker cartoonist has written a sort of graphic memoir about caring for her ailing parents.
snippet: The New Yorker cartoonist has written a sort of graphic memoir about caring for her ailing parents.
lead_paragraph: How did you pull this off, Roz Chast? How did you document the last eight years of your parents’ lives, in your distinctively doodle-ish drawings and candid prose, and make the story highly specific to their escape-from-the-Cossacks pasts in Brooklyn and, simultaneously, so universal? And how did you make this memoir — tellingly titled “Can’t We Talk About Something More Pleasant?” — both heartbreaking and snortingly funny?

abstract: How to write about public health issues without getting bogged down in cumbersome language and weighty data points.
snippet: How to write about public health issues without getting bogged down in cumbersome language and weighty data points.
lead_paragraph: A few years ago, while immersed in graduate studies in public health at the University of California, Berkeley, I wrote an article for a well-known general interest magazine about the H.I.V. epidemic among gay men in developing countries. I’d been a newspaper reporter for 10 years and had already written a couple of pieces for the publication, so I waited for an email gushing with praise for my thorough reporting and nimble prose.
headline.main: The Jargon Trap

abstract: The discovery will allow scientists to quickly, cheaply and easily test drugs that might stop the process in the first place.
snippet: The discovery will allow scientists to quickly, cheaply and easily test drugs that might stop the process in the first place.
lead_paragraph: For the first time, and to the astonishment of many of their colleagues, researchers created what they call Alzheimer’s in a Dish — a petri dish with human brain cells that develop the telltale structures of Alzheimer’s disease. In doing so, they resolved a longstanding problem of how to study Alzheimer’s and search for drugs to treat it; the best they had until now were mice that developed an imperfect form of the disease.

abstract: Many fear that Internet use is harming our mental capacity — but a new study shows it might actually help stave off the memory problems that come with age.
snippet: Many fear that Internet use is harming our mental capacity — but a new study shows it might actually help stave off the memory problems that come with age.
lead_paragraph: The Internet is frequently blamed for messing with our minds, making us superficial, distracted and even deluded. But a new study suggests that for some people, using it could actually be healthy.

headline.main: How the Internet Could Protect Your Memory

abstract: Josh Bennett, a high-fashion knitter, pushes the traditional boundaries of the craft.
snippet: Josh Bennett, a high-fashion knitter, pushes the traditional boundaries of the craft.
lead_paragraph: Forget the studies purporting to show that knitting can ease the somatic nervous system, reduce blood pressure, relax muscles and improve brain power while staving off dementia and reducing stress. Never mind the homely communitarianism of the all-male knitting circles that have popped up lately in bars and bookshops and under the trees in Bryant Park. Put aside the thrifty virtuousness of D.I.Y.

abstract: Residents sue a California retirement community after learning that refunds on entrance fees have not been set aside. Similar suits have cropped up elsewhere.
snippet: Residents sue a California retirement community after learning that refunds on entrance fees have not been set aside. Similar suits have cropped up elsewhere.
lead_paragraph: The way Burton Richter tells it, the house he and his wife had lived in for 40 years needed a fence repaired, and the repairman damaged the pool plumbing. Fixing that messed up the garden’s irrigation system. Soon afterward Dr. Richter had to climb onto the roof to repair a solar panel.

headline.main: C.C.R.C. Residents Ask, ‘Where’s the Money?’

abstract: Researchers are optimistic about recent efforts to delay the effects of aging and, perhaps, extend life spans.
snippet: Researchers are optimistic about recent efforts to delay the effects of aging and, perhaps, extend life spans.
lead_paragraph: For thousands of years, people have sought to escape or outrun their mortality with potions, pills and elixirs, often blended with heavy doses of hope and will.

abstract: A small but growing number of subsidized apartment complexes offer a welcoming environment to low- and moderate-income gay seniors, who often face housing discrimination.
snippet: A small but growing number of subsidized apartment complexes offer a welcoming environment to low- and moderate-income gay seniors, who often face housing discrimination.
lead_paragraph: PHILADELPHIA — DENISE SAMEN, who is 65 and a military veteran, has not had an easy life. She lost an arm in a train accident, supported herself by working a series of low-paying service and clerical jobs, needs a wheelchair to get around and came of age when homosexuality was considered a psychiatric disorder. And though she has never hidden who she is — she often dresses in men’s-styled clothing — she doesn’t play it up, either.

abstract: In the eight months since the operator of the Prospect Park Residence announced it was closing, the number of residents has dwindled to eight from more than 120, and most of the staff has left or been let go.
snippet: In the eight months since the operator of the Prospect Park Residence announced it was closing, the number of residents has dwindled to eight from more than 120, and most of the staff has left or been let go.
lead_paragraph: Mealtimes at the Prospect Park Residence, a building in the classical revival style overlooking Grand Army Plaza in Brooklyn, were once dignified affairs. The residents sat down to carefully folded napkins and pale-green tablecloths in a spacious dining room bustling with neighbors, medical aides and servers. The windows offered sweeping views of Prospect Park.

headline.main: At Assisted-Living Home Set to Close, Holdouts Dig In as Services Dry Up
headline.print_headline: At Assisted-Living Home Set to Close, Holdouts Dig in as Services Dry Up

abstract: Using cartoons, texts and photographs in “Can’t We Talk About Something More Pleasant?,” Roz Chast writes about her parents and dealing with their decline.
snippet: Using cartoons, texts and photographs in “Can’t We Talk About Something More Pleasant?,” Roz Chast writes about her parents and dealing with their decline.
lead_paragraph: Roz Chast feels — and draws — our pain. Our neurotic worries and genuine fears, our mundane and existential anxieties, our daydreams, nightmares, insecurities and guilty regrets. Or, rather, she does such a funny, fluent job in her New Yorker cartoons of conveying the things that keep her up at night that many readers are convinced that she is somehow mapping their own inner lives.

abstract: The authorities charged Johann Breyer was complicit in the gassing of 216,000 Jews brought to Auschwitz in 1944 from Hungary, Czechoslovakia and Germany.
snippet: The authorities charged Johann Breyer was complicit in the gassing of 216,000 Jews brought to Auschwitz in 1944 from Hungary, Czechoslovakia and Germany.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The 89-year-old Johann Breyer shuffled unsteadily into a federal courtroom in Philadelphia on Wednesday morning, using a cane for support as he sank slowly into a chair at the defense table.

abstract: Health care groups and members of Congress are opposing an Obama administration proposal to limit coverage for three classes of drugs.
snippet: Health care groups and members of Congress are opposing an Obama administration proposal to limit coverage for three classes of drugs.
lead_paragraph: An alliance of drug companies and patient advocates, joined by Democrats and Republicans in Congress, is fiercely opposing an Obama administration proposal that would allow insurers to limit Medicare coverage for certain classes of drugs, including those used to treat depression and schizophrenia.

abstract: Atul Gawande believes that the medical profession’s job is to “enable well-being,” not just strive for survival.
snippet: Atul Gawande believes that the medical profession’s job is to “enable well-being,” not just strive for survival.
lead_paragraph: It began with a tingle in the surgeon’s fingers and a pain in his neck. A couple of years later, he learned he had a tumor inside his spinal cord. That was when the difficult choices began. Should he have it removed right away in a risky operation, as his doctor recommended? Or should he take time to consider this question: At what point would the expanding tumor cause debility bad enough to justify the risk of greater debility or even death in trying to fight it?

abstract: The physical, emotional and financial changes that come with aging can lead to alcohol and, increasingly, drug addictions.
snippet: The physical, emotional and financial changes that come with aging can lead to alcohol and, increasingly, drug addictions.
lead_paragraph: BEFORE her drinking spiraled out of control, Sylvia Dobrow “drank like a lady,” as she put it, matching her wine to her sandwiches: “Tuna and chardonnay, roast beef and rosé.” But soon she was “drinking around the clock,” downing glasses of vodka and skim milk.

abstract: Residences near or on college campuses offer courses and culture for older adults.
snippet: Residences near or on college campuses offer courses and culture for older adults.
lead_paragraph: ARLENE AND LARRY DUNN, both music aficionados, had always been fans of two ensembles at the Oberlin College Conservatory of Music. So, the Dunns put the retirement community Kendal at Oberlin on the top of their list after they began looking for a new home. In addition to having a rich cultural life, the Dunns could audit Oberlin’s classes free and attend lectures. Last year, the Dunns sold their home in rural LaCrosse, Ind., and moved to the college community in neighboring Ohio.

abstract: Renée Fleming will sing “The Star-Spangled Banner” at the Super Bowl on Sunday, a first for an opera star.
snippet: Renée Fleming will sing “The Star-Spangled Banner” at the Super Bowl on Sunday, a first for an opera star.
lead_paragraph: Since 1967, the national anthem has been sung at the Super Bowl by a boy band and a college a cappella group. It has been belted by a morning-TV host and bugled by a trumpeter (four times!).

abstract: Thad Cochran, the six-term Republican senator from Mississippi, defeated a Tea Party challenger in a runoff after a campaign for which he sometimes showed little enthusiasm.
snippet: Thad Cochran, the six-term Republican senator from Mississippi, defeated a Tea Party challenger in a runoff after a campaign for which he sometimes showed little enthusiasm.
lead_paragraph: JACKSON, Miss. — The question seemed to tug at Senator Thad Cochran throughout his bumpy re-election campaign in Mississippi: Why, after a long, distinguished career — 42 years in Congress, including six terms in the Senate — was he seeking a seventh term?

abstract: Seeing Dad for the last time was both a blessing and a curse.
snippet: Seeing Dad for the last time was both a blessing and a curse.
lead_paragraph: IT’S been eight years since I last saw my father, lying in his reclining chair in his living room, as perfectly still as the half-filled coffee cups on the side table.

abstract: An adviser to politicians and businessmen, Mr. Burke became president of CBS News and was appointed chairman of the Broadcasting Board of Governors by President Bill Clinton.
snippet: An adviser to politicians and businessmen, Mr. Burke became president of CBS News and was appointed chairman of the Broadcasting Board of Governors by President Bill Clinton.
lead_paragraph: Senator Edward M. Kennedy had a habit of taking long walks with his closest aide, David W. Burke, before making big decisions. As secretary to Gov. Hugh L. Carey, Mr. Burke helped New York City navigate the 1970s fiscal crisis, partly by recommending that he hire Felix Rohatyn as financial wizard in chief.

abstract: The enthusiastic amateurs, Christian conservatives and Tea Party activists supporting Chris McDaniel stand in contrast to his rival Senator Thad Cochran’s establishment backing.
snippet: The enthusiastic amateurs, Christian conservatives and Tea Party activists supporting Chris McDaniel stand in contrast to his rival Senator Thad Cochran’s establishment backing.
lead_paragraph: JACKSON, Miss. — It is still not entirely clear what three supporters of the Tea Party favorite Chris McDaniel were doing locked in at 3 a.m. in a darkened courthouse where votes had been tabulated on the night of the state’s contentious primary election last week.

abstract: The “Good Morning America” anchor and author of “Everybody’s Got Something” calls Maya Angelou her literary hero: As a teenager in Mississippi, “I identified with her quest for independence.”

abstract: Advice to help older adults avoid financial abuse from those they trust.
snippet: Advice to help older adults avoid financial abuse from those they trust.
lead_paragraph: WHEN a longtime friend asked for a loan to help get her boyfriend back on his feet, Maria Voltl, 84, decided to help. Ms. Voltl had lent money to her friend before, and it had always been paid back. So without consulting a professional, she handed over $500,000.

headline.main: Financial Schemes Against the Elderly Are Increasing
headline.print_headline: Older, Vulnerable and Swindled by Those They Loved

abstract: Elderly people need everyday help, and there aren’t enough humans to provide it.
snippet: Elderly people need everyday help, and there aren’t enough humans to provide it.
lead_paragraph: EACH time I make a house call, I stay much longer than I should. I can’t leave because my patient is holding my hand, or because she’s telling me, not for the first time, about when Aunt Mabel cut off all her hair and they called her a boy at school, or how her daddy lost his job and the lights went out and her mother lit pine cones and danced and made everyone laugh. Sometimes I can’t leave because she just has to show me one thing, but getting to that thing requires that she rise unsteadily from her chair, negotiate her walker through the narrow hallway, and find whatever it is in the dim light of her bedroom.

abstract: Phil Jackson, who will be introduced Tuesday at Madison Square Garden, took to Twitter last summer in support of the triangle offense, which he could bring to the Knicks.
snippet: Phil Jackson, who will be introduced Tuesday at Madison Square Garden, took to Twitter last summer in support of the triangle offense, which he could bring to the Knicks.
lead_paragraph: People tend to listen when Phil Jackson talks, or tweets, even in August, traditionally the N.B.A.’s tune-out season.

abstract: Demand is up, and so is supply at Litchfield.
snippet: Demand is up, and so is supply at Litchfield.
lead_paragraph: Season 2, Episode 7 The world is too much with our friends at Litchfield as their various commercial enterprises kick into high gear. And this episode, “Comic Sans,” brings the mounting sense that all this getting and spending will not end well.

abstract: Exactly 1,809 days after he was captured, Sgt. Bowe Bergdahl returned to a homecoming void of any relatives and dampened by a controversy over his capture and release.
snippet: Exactly 1,809 days after he was captured, Sgt. Bowe Bergdahl returned to a homecoming void of any relatives and dampened by a controversy over his capture and release.
lead_paragraph: SAN ANTONIO — Exactly 1,809 days after he was captured by Taliban fighters who kept him in a metal cage for weeks and possibly months during nearly five years in captivity, Sgt. Bowe Bergdahl returned to the United States early Friday to a homecoming void of any of his relatives and dampened by a swirling controversy over his capture and release.

abstract: Senator Thad Cochran appeared headed for a runoff with a Tea Party-backed challenger in Mississippi, while in Iowa, State Senator Joni Ernst cruised to victory.
snippet: Senator Thad Cochran appeared headed for a runoff with a Tea Party-backed challenger in Mississippi, while in Iowa, State Senator Joni Ernst cruised to victory.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — There was no clear winner early Wednesday in the most hard-fought Republican Senate primary race this year, with the six-term incumbent Thad Cochran of Mississippi and his Tea Party-backed challenger, State Senator Chris McDaniel, running neck and neck after a night of lead changes.

abstract: It took the courts nearly half a century to conclude that the evidence against him was likely fabricated by police investigators and to order the retrial he sought.
snippet: It took the courts nearly half a century to conclude that the evidence against him was likely fabricated by police investigators and to order the retrial he sought.
lead_paragraph: TOKYO — Iwao Hakamada was a wiry former boxer in his 30s when he was thrown in jail for the killing of a family of four that shocked 1960s Japan. On Thursday, he limped from his cell on death row, a bewildered-looking 78-year-old who, his family fears, may have lost his mind in prison.

abstract: The eccentric scion of a prominent Dallas family that made a fortune in oil, Mr. Hunt tried and failed to corner the world’s silver market in 1980.
snippet: The eccentric scion of a prominent Dallas family that made a fortune in oil, Mr. Hunt tried and failed to corner the world’s silver market in 1980.
lead_paragraph: Nelson Bunker Hunt, the down-home Texas oil tycoon who owned a thousand race horses, drove an old Cadillac and once tried to corner the world’s silver market only to lose most of his fortune when the price collapsed, died on Tuesday in Dallas. He was 88.

abstract: Chuck Klosterman writes the Ethicist column for The Times Magazine. Here he reflects on the experience.
snippet: Chuck Klosterman writes the Ethicist column for The Times Magazine. Here he reflects on the experience.
lead_paragraph: Chuck Klosterman is an author, essayist and former rock critic. He writes The Ethicist, a weekly column for The Times Magazine. His responses have sometimes provoked outrage. Klosterman isn’t surprised. We asked him to reflect on writing the column.

abstract: Modern advances being applied to historical crimes include virtual models of Nazi camps to demonstrate what guards would have been able to see from their posts.
snippet: Modern advances being applied to historical crimes include virtual models of Nazi camps to demonstrate what guards would have been able to see from their posts.
lead_paragraph: STUTTGART, Germany — After years of relative inaction, German prosecutors have opened dozens of fresh investigations of men and women suspected of having served as Nazi death camp guards, racing against the clock to bring the aging suspects to justice. Not since the end of World War II have so many cases been initiated at once.

abstract: Mr. García Márquez, who received the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1982, wrote fiction rooted in a mythical Latin American landscape of his own creation.
snippet: Mr. García Márquez, who received the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1982, wrote fiction rooted in a mythical Latin American landscape of his own creation.
lead_paragraph: Gabriel García Márquez, the Colombian novelist whose “One Hundred Years of Solitude” established him as a giant of 20th-century literature, died on Thursday at his home in Mexico City. He was 87.

abstract: Like hundreds of women during the Civil War, Jennie Hodgers disguised herself as a man in order to fight. Unlike most others, though, after the war ended, her cover remained.
snippet: Like hundreds of women during the Civil War, Jennie Hodgers disguised herself as a man in order to fight. Unlike most others, though, after the war ended, her cover remained.
lead_paragraph: In the spring of 1914, a Civil War veteran named Albert Cashier arrived at the Illinois state hospital for the insane with symptoms of advanced dementia. As a young private, Cashier had fought at the siege of Vicksburg, where he and his comrades broke the spine of the Confederacy, and his name was inscribed on the Illinois victory monument there. He had lived out the intervening years in modest circumstances, working as a farm hand, a laborer and, on occasion, a street lamplighter, one of the many former soldiers whose civilian lives never achieve the glory of their wartime service. He was destined for the same obscurity in death, had it not been for a secret that the state hospital made public: Albert Cashier was actually a woman named Jennie Hodgers.
headline.main: Albert Cashier’s Secret

abstract: Banks tend to take a defensive view of people with power of attorney for fear of litigation. Any discrepancy will gum up the works.
snippet: Banks tend to take a defensive view of people with power of attorney for fear of litigation. Any discrepancy will gum up the works.
lead_paragraph: FOR millions of people over the decades, the power of attorney has been an inexpensive way to give someone the right to act on another person’s behalf. But its power is not always absolute and when it fails, the consequences can be nothing short of disastrous.
headline.main: Power of Attorney Is Not Always a Solution
headline.print_headline: Power of Attorney Is Not Always a Solution

abstract: A California-based home care company is pondering three choices in meeting new state and federal work rules regarding its caregivers.
snippet: A California-based home care company is pondering three choices in meeting new state and federal work rules regarding its caregivers.
lead_paragraph: SELECT HOME CARE, based in Westlake Village, Calif., offers 24-hour nonmedical care to elderly clients in California, Nevada, Utah, Colorado, Oregon and Texas. It has nine offices, 500 employees and more than $10 million in annual revenue.

abstract: The documentary, directed by James Keach, follows Glen Campbell’s final tour, as he and his family deal with his decline from Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: The documentary, directed by James Keach, follows Glen Campbell’s final tour, as he and his family deal with his decline from Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: From the very first scene, “I’ll Be Me” signals that it is not going to be a conventional documentary about a celebrity, in this case the country-pop singer and guitarist Glen Campbell. As Mr. Campbell sits in a darkened room watching home movies of his younger self, he asks his wife, Kim, “Who is that?”

headline.print_headline: A Farewell to His Fans and Himself

abstract: The Bay Area plays a big part in a couple’s romance.
snippet: The Bay Area plays a big part in a couple’s romance.
lead_paragraph: Though Stephanie Rosenbaum had led more than 100 food tours of San Francisco, she rarely saw a single man older than 40 take part. Mainly women and couples wanted her insider’s take on the city’s food scene.

abstract: The legendary Washington Post editor knew how to mentor a kid from nowhere. Next to my father, he was the most important man in my life.
snippet: The legendary Washington Post editor knew how to mentor a kid from nowhere. Next to my father, he was the most important man in my life.
lead_paragraph: I first met Ben Bradlee in the winter of 1969. I was a 19-year-old kid from Canton, Ohio, who had never taken a course in journalism, never published an article, rarely read the newspaper and had little notion of what I would do with my life. Yet somehow as a Brandeis sophomore I had made my way to be a finalist for the Washington Post internship. It must have been my essay. And there I was sitting at Ben Bradlee’s right hand in a Boston restaurant surrounded by other finalists, all of whom went to Harvard, were working on The Crimson, and had dazzling credentials. By the time lunch was over, I was sure I was no longer in the running. But as I got up to leave, Ben placed his hand on my arm and asked me if I had a few minutes to talk. A half-hour passed. He asked me what I thought of the Vietnam War. I remember telling him I was torn. He seemed pleased by my confusion. We talked about writing. I honestly don’t remember what else we talked about except that when we parted I knew what I wanted to do — I wanted to work for him. (Mind you, that was two years before Watergate.)
headline.main: The Ben Bradlee Who Hired Me — Finally
headline.print_headline: The Ben Bradlee Who Hired Me — Finally

abstract: “Audubon’s Aviary: Parts Unknown” at the New-York Historical Society shows John James Audubon as an established artist-naturalist with the zeal of an amateur and the curiosity of a scientist.
snippet: “Audubon’s Aviary: Parts Unknown” at the New-York Historical Society shows John James Audubon as an established artist-naturalist with the zeal of an amateur and the curiosity of a scientist.
lead_paragraph: I’ve never met an animal I didn’t like. And birds? Bring them on, which is what the New-York Historical Society is doing with a whoosh of wings and cries in “Audubon’s Aviary: Parts Unknown (Part II of the Complete Flock),” the second of three sequential exhibitions of the museum’s complete set of more than 400 paintings by John James Audubon, all models for his grand book “The Birds of America.” It is widely regarded as the most ambitious example of color engraving with aquatint ever made.

abstract: A journey taken with a woman and her dying father led Nina Bernstein to write an article that speaks to the challenges many readers also face.
snippet: A journey taken with a woman and her dying father led Nina Bernstein to write an article that speaks to the challenges many readers also face.
lead_paragraph: The photograph is beautifully composed, like an old masters painting of a biblical deathbed scene: An aged man looks to his daughter for an answer; the daughter’s upward glance conveys her struggle to find the right one.

headline.main: To Die at Home:  Reporter’s Notebook

abstract: Managers at the Prospect Park Residence in Brooklyn, which is home to about 120 seniors, surprised residents when they announced that financial problems are forcing them to close the building.
snippet: Managers at the Prospect Park Residence in Brooklyn, which is home to about 120 seniors, surprised residents when they announced that financial problems are forcing them to close the building.
lead_paragraph: Outside the elevator doors where residents congregate with their walkers, in the big white dining room and in the floral-carpeted hallways where aides push wheelchairs along, it has been all anyone can talk about.

abstract: There is no rigorous scientific evidence that marijuana effectively treats the symptoms of many of the illnesses for which states have authorized its use.
snippet: There is no rigorous scientific evidence that marijuana effectively treats the symptoms of many of the illnesses for which states have authorized its use.
lead_paragraph: New York moved last week to join 22 states in legalizing medical marijuana for patients with a diverse array of debilitating ailments, encompassing epilepsy and cancer, Crohn’s disease and Parkinson’s. Yet there is no rigorous scientific evidence that marijuana effectively treats the symptoms of many of the illnesses for which states have authorized its use.

abstract: Ms. Kizer was known for political and satirical works that, she said, came with “a sting in the tail.”
snippet: Ms. Kizer was known for political and satirical works that, she said, came with “a sting in the tail.”
lead_paragraph: Carolyn Kizer, a Pulitzer Prize-winning poet whose verse, overtly political and bitingly satirical, came, as she fondly put it, with “a sting in the tail,” died on Thursday in Sonoma, Calif. She was 89.

abstract: With a push for change from lawmakers, players and doctors, and from discussions with the same experts who brought the issue to the fore in the United States, the topic is gaining momentum.
snippet: With a push for change from lawmakers, players and doctors, and from discussions with the same experts who brought the issue to the fore in the United States, the topic is gaining momentum.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — The debate over how to respond to the growing research linking brain trauma to injuries sustained in sports has spread to Europe, with many of the same dynamics seen in recent years as the issue gained momentum in the United States.

abstract: The photographer Duane Michals talks about his art and the new retrospective of his work at the Carnegie Museum of Art in Pittsburgh.
snippet: The photographer Duane Michals talks about his art and the new retrospective of his work at the Carnegie Museum of Art in Pittsburgh.
lead_paragraph: McKEESPORT, Pa. — It’s a bright September morning in this Pittsburgh suburb, but Duane Michals ought to be blue. He’s on a visit to the house where he was born 82 years ago, the son of a millworker father. But the mills have closed, whole blocks are returning to nature, and Mr. Michals has just discovered that his home has collapsed into a tangle of lumber and weeds.
headline.main: Documents of a Contrarian
headline.print_headline: Documents of a Contrarian

abstract: I always knew I’d die, without knowing when. But now I knew it acutely.
snippet: I always knew I’d die, without knowing when. But now I knew it acutely.
lead_paragraph: AS soon as the CT scan was done, I began reviewing the images. The diagnosis was immediate: Masses matting the lungs and deforming the spine. Cancer. In my neurosurgical training, I had reviewed hundreds of scans for fellow doctors to see if surgery offered any hope. I’d scribble in the chart “Widely metastatic disease — no role for surgery,” and move on. But this scan was different: It was my own.

abstract: Lynne Ditman and Richard Goldberg met when they were 17, but they did not revive their romance until after more than 40 years apart.
snippet: Lynne Ditman and Richard Goldberg met when they were 17, but they did not revive their romance until after more than 40 years apart.
lead_paragraph: When Lynne Kornreich met Richard Goldberg, they were both 17, and it was the ’60s, but not the Swinging Sixties. She was a waitress and he was a busboy at the Sinclair Hotel in Bethlehem, N.H., which was the sort of resort one would have found in that era in the Catskills — where Melba toast and cottage cheese were once popular mainstays, and everyone ate as if it were the last meal.

abstract: The suicide of a Mississippi Tea Party founder who was charged in a plot to photograph Senator Thad Cochran’s ailing wife has deepened the enmity left by a divisive Republican primary.
snippet: The suicide of a Mississippi Tea Party founder who was charged in a plot to photograph Senator Thad Cochran’s ailing wife has deepened the enmity left by a divisive Republican primary.
lead_paragraph: JACKSON, Miss. — Mark Mayfield, one of the founders of the Mississippi Tea Party, had lost his political appetite.

abstract: Rochelle Sterling, wife of the beleaguered Donald Sterling, said she would fight to maintain ownership of the franchise, saying, “If the roles were reversed, would they take the team away from the man?”
snippet: Rochelle Sterling, wife of the beleaguered Donald Sterling, said she would fight to maintain ownership of the franchise, saying, “If the roles were reversed, would they take the team away from the man?”
lead_paragraph: As co-owner of the Los Angeles Clippers for the past 33 years, Rochelle Sterling has been a largely silent partner. But now, as the N.B.A. pushes for the permanent removal of her husband, she does not want to go away quietly.

abstract: The industry and the players may have grown too large for the game to be played safely.
snippet: The industry and the players may have grown too large for the game to be played safely.
lead_paragraph: In the summer of 1978, during a preseason game, a wide receiver for the New England Patriots named Darryl Stingley lunged for a pass just out of his reach. Before he could regain his balance, he was hit by Jack Tatum, an Oakland Raiders defensive back. It was clear at once that Stingley was, in gridiron parlance, “shaken up on the play.” Team doctors rushed to his side.

abstract: Mr. Marshall, along with one of Brooke Astor’s former lawyers, was found guilty of criminal charges that they swindled millions from her after she was stricken with Alzheimer’s disease.
snippet: Mr. Marshall, along with one of Brooke Astor’s former lawyers, was found guilty of criminal charges that they swindled millions from her after she was stricken with Alzheimer’s disease.
lead_paragraph: Anthony D. Marshall, the only son of the philanthropist-socialite Brooke Astor, who with one of her former lawyers was found guilty of criminal charges that they swindled millions from his mother after she was stricken with Alzheimer’s disease, died on Sunday in Manhattan. He was 90.

abstract: When it comes to concussions and their lasting effects, Nascar drivers are largely on their own, though a new coalition of top teams may represent hope for help.
snippet: When it comes to concussions and their lasting effects, Nascar drivers are largely on their own, though a new coalition of top teams may represent hope for help.
lead_paragraph: Talladega Superspeedway is known on the Nascar circuit for high speeds, packs of cars racing inches apart and spectacular multicar wrecks that fans love and drivers endure. A crash occurs during almost every race at Talladega, a huge Alabama oval, like the one in the final laps of a Nationwide Series event there in May 2012.

abstract: New books include Jeff VanderMeer’s “Authority,” the second novel in a trilogy about an ecological danger zone.
snippet: New books include Jeff VanderMeer’s “Authority,” the second novel in a trilogy about an ecological danger zone.
lead_paragraph: In “Annihilation,” the first book of Jeff VanderMeer’s Southern Reach trilogy, readers were introduced to Area X, a stretch of coastal wetland whose conspiracy-theory name is the icing atop a mille-feuille of layered, slow-building, deliciously creepy horror. Twelve teams of ­researchers, stripped of names to somehow protect them from the identity-warping effects of the danger zone, have traveled into Area X; “Annihilation” followed “the biologist” as she seemingly became the only survivor to actually understand what was happening.

abstract: Project ECHO is a “disruptive innovation” that uses video to train clinicians to perform like specialists in underserved areas. Used more widely it could transform health care.
snippet: Project ECHO is a “disruptive innovation” that uses video to train clinicians to perform like specialists in underserved areas. Used more widely it could transform health care.
lead_paragraph: Ten years ago Dr. Sanjeev Arora, a hepatologist at the University of New Mexico in Albuquerque, realized that he would need to change the way he practiced medicine if he was going to prevent his patients from dying.

headline.main: The Power to Cure, Multiplied

abstract: Maureen Stefanides wanted to fulfill her father’s request after long nursing home stays left him weak and unhappy, but the forces of the health care system seemed stacked against her.
snippet: Maureen Stefanides wanted to fulfill her father’s request after long nursing home stays left him weak and unhappy, but the forces of the health care system seemed stacked against her.
lead_paragraph: Joseph Andrey was 5 years old in 1927 when his impoverished mother sold him to the manager of a popular vaudeville act. He was 91 last year when he told the story again, propped in a wheelchair in the rehabilitation unit of a nursing home where it seemed as though age and infirmity had put a different kind of price on his head.

headline.main: Fighting to Honor a Father’s Last Wish: To Die at Home
headline.print_headline: A Father’s Last Wish, and a Daughter’s Anguish

abstract: When Chris Snee visited Giants Coach Tom Coughlin last summer to talk about retiring from football, the coach saw the father of his three grandchildren, not a Pro Bowl lineman.
snippet: When Chris Snee visited Giants Coach Tom Coughlin last summer to talk about retiring from football, the coach saw the father of his three grandchildren, not a Pro Bowl lineman.
lead_paragraph: In July, Giants Coach Tom Coughlin was vacationing on the lush coast of Georgia with Chris Snee, who for the past 10 years had been Coughlin’s starting right guard and his son-in-law.

abstract: A critical guide to productions in New York City, including shows in previews.

lead_paragraph: Approximate running times are in parentheses. Theaters are in Manhattan unless otherwise noted. Full reviews of current productions, additional listings, showtimes and ticket information are at nytimes.com/theater. A searchable, critical guide to theater is at nytimes.com/events.

abstract: A guide to theater productions in New York City, with a special note of shows in previews or about to open.
snippet: A guide to theater productions in New York City, with a special note of shows in previews or about to open.
lead_paragraph: Approximate running times are in parentheses. Theaters are in Manhattan unless otherwise noted. Full reviews of current productions, additional listings, showtimes and ticket information are at nytimes.com/theater. A searchable, critical guide to theater is at nytimes.com/events.

abstract: A critical guide to productions in New York City, including shows in previews.
snippet: A critical guide to productions in New York City, including shows in previews.
lead_paragraph: Approximate running times are in parentheses. Theaters are in Manhattan unless otherwise noted. Full reviews of current productions, additional listings, showtimes and ticket information are at nytimes.com/theater. A searchable, critical guide to theater is at nytimes.com/events.

abstract: A critical guide to productions in New York City, including shows in previews.
snippet: A critical guide to productions in New York City, including shows in previews.
lead_paragraph: Approximate running times are in parentheses. Theaters are in Manhattan unless otherwise noted. Full reviews of current productions, additional listings, showtimes and ticket information are at nytimes.com/theater. A searchable, critical guide to theater is at nytimes.com/events.

headline.main: Fall Arts Preview - Film

abstract: Listings of this summer’s releases.
snippet: Listings of this summer’s releases.
lead_paragraph: Yes, Scarlett Johansson wakes up with superpowers and takes no prisoners, but the season isn’t totally about would-be action blockbusters. Philip Seymour Hoffman gifts us with two posthumous performances, as a blue-collar American loser and as a powerful German spy. Documentaries explore a dizzying range of topics, including legal marijuana, the war in Afghanistan, breast-feeding and the Koch brothers. And climate change rears its plot-driving head, ready to replace midcentury nuclear testing as the villain in sci-fi and futurist fantasies.
headline.main: Summer Movie Release Schedule
headline.print_headline: Witches, Monsters and Men in Tights

abstract: The mass abduction of schoolgirls from a dormitory in Nigeria by Boko Haram is outrageous and needs to be condemned globally.
snippet: The mass abduction of schoolgirls from a dormitory in Nigeria by Boko Haram is outrageous and needs to be condemned globally.
lead_paragraph: Re “What’s so scary about smart girls?” (May 12): Nicholas Kristof’s invitation to stick it to extremist groups like Boko Haram by helping to educate girls should be considered cautiously. We need to do everything we can to educate girls without making them easy targets by buying school uniforms that could incite more abductions or by operating schools in high risk areas. Recent grass-roots efforts to bring attention to these atrocities, an accountable government and a fair criminal justice system may be the most effective sticks against emboldened terrorists who feel threatened by women fulfilling their highest potential. Achieving this will be an enormous challenge, but getting there will be much easier with inspirational leaders like Angeline Mugwendere and Malala Yousafzai.
headline.main: The Stolen Nigerian Schoolgirls
